{"title_page": "Bad Choice Road", "text_new": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = Bad Choice \n| series         = [[Better Call Saul]]\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| season         = 5\n| episode        = 9\n| editor         = \n| airdate        = {{Start date|2020|4|13}}\n| writer         = [[Thomas Schnauz]]\n| director       = [[Thomas Schnauz]]\n| length         = 53 minutes\n| guests         = \n| music          = \n| prev           = [[Bagman (Better Call Saul)|Bagman]]\n| next           = [[Something Unforgivable]]\n| episode_list   = List of Better Call Saul episodes\n| season_article = Better Call Saul (season 5)\n}}\n\n\"'''Bad Choice Road'''\" is the ninth episode of the [[Better Call Saul (season 5)|fifth season]] of the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] television series ''[[Better Call Saul]]'', the spinoff series of ''[[Breaking Bad]]''. The episode aired on April 13, 2020 on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] in the United States. Outside of the United States, the episode premiered on streaming service [[Netflix]] in several countries.\n\n== Plot ==\nJimmy and Mike trek out of the desert until Jimmy manages to get cell phone signal, and he calls a relieved Kim to tell her he's safe. They are picked up by Tyrus and Victor at a truck stop. Mike arranges to have the attackers' trucks and bodies removed, and gives Jimmy a cover story about his car breaking down a few miles from the pickup point and walking all night before finding a truck stop. \n\nJimmy turns the money to the bail office to release Lalo, which draws the district attorney's attention. Jimmy goes to meet Lalo when he is released, giving him the cover story, and warns him about the attention on his alias. Lalo assures Jimmy he will be in Mexico soon enough.  Jimmy returns home, where he gives the same story to Kim as she tends to his wounds. He scolds her about seeing Lalo. When she checks on the fee Jimmy got, she finds the bullet-ridden mug she had given Jimmy. Meanwhile, Mike reports to Gus on the attack, who affirms it was arranged by Juan Bolsa, attempting to protect Gus's business. Mike warns Gus that Nacho wants out of the operation, but Gus refuses.\n\nThe next day, Jimmy is still shaken by events and Kim calls in sick to help care for him. She knows his cover story was false but won't judge him if he comes clean, but he eludes her as he runs off to handle a client at the courthouse. She tries to do work at S&C but makes the decision to quit her job, otherwise keeping her ''pro bono'' work. Jimmy later meets with Mike, struggling with the trauma. Mike tells him that these bad choices they have made will lead to the same roads, providing little solace.\n\nAfter seeing Hector, Lalo has Nacho take him to the same dropoff spot he gave Jimmy near the Mexico border, unaware they are tracked by Victor. There, Lalo gets an idea and has Nacho follow the road back to Albuquerque, where they find Jimmy's shot-up car.\n\nKim tells Jimmy about quitting S&C that evening, which Jimmy scolds her for, just as both Jimmy's cell rings and a knock is at the door. Jimmy finds Mike on the cell line, telling him to leave the phone on and out of sight, while Kim tells Jimmy to come to the door. There, Lalo comes in, settles down, and asks Jimmy to repeat his cover story several times, while Mike listens and watches from a distance with a sniper rifle trained on Lalo. Each time Lalo asks, Jimmy's version changes. Eventually, Lalo reveals he saw the shot-up car, but Kim steps in and tells Lalo that Jimmy was just doing his job as his lawyer, and the car likely shot at by passersby. Lalo quietly leaves, and tells Nacho to drive all the way into Mexico.\n\n== Production ==\n\n\n== Reception ==\n\n\n=== Ratings ===\n\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.amc.com/shows/better-call-saul/season-5/episode-09-bad-choice-road \"Bad Choice Road\"] at [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n*{{IMDb episode|8772220}}\n\n{{Better Call Saul}}\n\n[[Category:Better Call Saul (season 5) episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = Bad Choice \n| series         = [[Better Call Saul]]\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| season         = 5\n| episode        = 9\n| editor         = \n| airdate        = {{Start date|2020|4|12}}\n| writer         = [[Thomas Schnauz]]\n| director       = [[Thomas Schnauz]]\n| length         = 53 minutes\n| guests         = \n| music          = \n| prev           = [[Bagman (Better Call Saul)|Bagman]]\n| next           = [[Something Unforgivable]]\n| episode_list   = List of Better Call Saul episodes\n| season_article = Better Call Saul (season 5)\n}}\n\n\"'''Bad Choice Road'''\" is the ninth episode of the [[Better Call Saul (season 5)|fifth season]] of the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] television series ''[[Better Call Saul]]'', the spinoff series of ''[[Breaking Bad]]''. The episode aired on April 13, 2020 on [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] in the United States. Outside of the United States, the episode premiered on streaming service [[Netflix]] in several countries.\n\n== Plot ==\nJimmy and Mike trek out of the desert until Jimmy manages to get cell phone signal, and he calls a relieved Kim to tell her he's safe. They are picked up by Tyrus and Victor at a truck stop. Mike arranges to have the attackers' trucks and bodies removed, and gives Jimmy a cover story about his car breaking down a few miles from the pickup point and walking all night before finding a truck stop. \n\nJimmy turns the money to the bail office to release Lalo, which draws the district attorney's attention. Jimmy goes to meet Lalo when he is released, giving him the cover story, and warns him about the attention on his alias. Lalo assures Jimmy he will be in Mexico soon enough.  Jimmy returns home, where he gives the same story to Kim as she tends to his wounds. He scolds her about seeing Lalo. When she checks on the fee Jimmy got, she finds the bullet-ridden mug she had given Jimmy. Meanwhile, Mike reports to Gus on the attack, who affirms it was arranged by Juan Bolsa, attempting to protect Gus's business. Mike warns Gus that Nacho wants out of the operation, but Gus refuses.\n\nThe next day, Jimmy is still shaken by events and Kim calls in sick to help care for him. She knows his cover story was false but won't judge him if he comes clean, but he eludes her as he runs off to handle a client at the courthouse. She tries to do work at S&C but makes the decision to quit her job, otherwise keeping her ''pro bono'' work. Jimmy later meets with Mike, struggling with the trauma. Mike tells him that these bad choices they have made will lead to the same roads, providing little solace.\n\nAfter seeing Hector, Lalo has Nacho take him to the same dropoff spot he gave Jimmy near the Mexico border, unaware they are tracked by Victor. There, Lalo gets an idea and has Nacho follow the road back to Albuquerque, where they find Jimmy's shot-up car.\n\nKim tells Jimmy about quitting S&C that evening, which Jimmy scolds her for, just as both Jimmy's cell rings and a knock is at the door. Jimmy finds Mike on the cell line, telling him to leave the phone on and out of sight, while Kim tells Jimmy to come to the door. There, Lalo comes in, settles down, and asks Jimmy to repeat his cover story several times, while Mike listens and watches from a distance with a sniper rifle trained on Lalo. Each time Lalo asks, Jimmy's version changes. Eventually, Lalo reveals he saw the shot-up car, but Kim steps in and tells Lalo that Jimmy was just doing his job as his lawyer, and the car likely shot at by passersby. Lalo quietly leaves, and tells Nacho to drive all the way into Mexico.\n\n== Production ==\n\n\n== Reception ==\n\n\n=== Ratings ===\n\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.amc.com/shows/better-call-saul/season-5/episode-09-bad-choice-road \"Bad Choice Road\"] at [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]]\n*{{IMDb episode|8772220}}\n\n{{Better Call Saul}}\n\n[[Category:Better Call Saul (season 5) episodes]]\n", "name_user": "Masem", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bad_Choice_Road"}
{"title_page": "Timeline of the 2020 United States presidential election", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = Timeline of the 2020 United States presidential election\n| country = USA\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = Timeline of the 2016 United States presidential election\n| previous_year = 2016\n| next_election = Timeline of the 2024 United States presidential election\n| next_year = 2024\n}}\n{{US 2020 presidential elections series}}\nThe following is a '''timeline of major events''' leading up, during, and after the United States presidential election of 2020. President [[Donald Trump]] of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], who was elected in [[2016 United States presidential election|2016]], is seeking reelection to a second term. The [[2020 United States presidential election|election]] is the 59th [[quadrennial]] [[United States presidential election]] and is scheduled to be held on November 3, 2020. The [[United States presidential primary|presidential primaries and caucuses]] are scheduled to be held between February and June 2020, staggered among the 50 states, [[Washington, D.C.]], and U.S. territories. The [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] is scheduled to certify the electoral result on January 5, 2021, and the new or incumbent president and vice president will be [[United States presidential inauguration|inaugurated]] on January 20, 2021.\n\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n== 2017 ==\n[[File:John Delaney (46743402692).jpg|thumb|[[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]] was the first major Democratic candidate to announce his campaign on July 28, 2017]]\n\n*'''February 17''': Republican incumbent president [[Donald Trump]] informally announces his candidacy for a second term and holds the first of a series of occasional reelection campaign rallies in [[Melbourne, Florida]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Superville|first1=Darlene|last2=Riechmann|first2=Deb|title=Outside of Washington, Trump slips back into campaign mode|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2017/02/18/outside-washington-trump-slips-back-into-campaign-mode.html|website=Fox News|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=March 5, 2017|location=West Palm Beach, Florida|date=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n*'''July 28''': Representative [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]] of Maryland officially announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/politics/blog/bs-md-delaney-announcement-20170728-story.html |title=Delaney announces campaign for president, becomes first to challenge Trump |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |date=July 28, 2017 |accessdate=December 11, 2018 |first=John |last=Fritze}}</ref> breaking the record for the earliest official presidential candidacy declaration in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailykos.com/story/2017/7/29/1685409/-John-Delaney-s-Presidential-Campaign-Announcement-is-the-Earliest-in-History|title=John Delaney's Presidential Campaign Announcement is the Earliest in History|website=Daily Kos|access-date=August 3, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''November 6''': Tech entrepreneur [[Andrew Yang]] of [[New York (state)|New York]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/03/politics/2020-dem-announcements/index.html|title=Here's how 2020 Democrats announced their campaigns |work=[[CNN]]|date=February 13, 2019| first=Schwarz|last= Hunter}}</ref>\n\n== 2018 ==\n*'''January 16''': Anti-war activist [[Adam Kokesh]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Libertarian Party. Hours after the announcement, he was pulled over twice and subsequently arrested on [[drug possession|possession]]-related charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/2018/01/20/hours-after-declaring-candidacy-presidential-hopeful-arrested-in-wise-county/|title=Hours after declaring candidacy, presidential hopeful arrested in Wise County|date=January 19, 2018|author=Ramirez, Marc|accessdate=October 6, 2019|work=[[The Dallas Morning News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.star-telegram.com/news/local/fort-worth/article195357574.html|title=He announced his candidacy for president. 30 minutes later, he was arrested|author=Hanna, Bill|date=January 18, 2018|accessdate=October 6, 2019|work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]}}</ref>\n*'''May 3''': The [[Republican National Committee]] eliminates their debate committee for the 2020 election cycle, signaling that that they do not plan to sanction any debates between Trump and possible primary challengers.<ref>{{cite new |title=Republican Party nixes debate committee ahead of 2020|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/03/politics/rnc-2020-debates/index.html|last=Berg |first=Rebecca|publisher=CNN|date=May 3, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''July 3''': Former [[Libertarian National Committee]] vice-chair [[Arvin Vohra]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Libertarian Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://reason.com/2018/07/06/controversialist-arvin-vohra-announces-2/|title=Controversialist Arvin Vohra Announces 2020 Libertarian Presidential Run|author=Welch, Matt|date=July 6, 2018|accessdate=October 6, 2019|work=[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]}}</ref>\n*'''July 18''': [[Charlotte, North Carolina]] is chosen as the host city of the [[2020 Republican National Convention]]<ref name=\"RNC-Charlotte\">{{cite web|url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/politics-government/rnc-2020/article215204290.html|title=GOP picks Charlotte for 2020 convention. Now, the fundraising and organizing begin.|date=July 20, 2018|first=Jim|last=Morill|work=[[The Charlotte Observer]]|accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''August 25''': Democratic Party officials and television networks begin discussions as to the nature and scheduling of the following year's debates and the nomination process.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/5068444bc8d549229b1c2b8fb079055b|title=APNewsBreak: DNC, TV networks discuss presidential debates|date=August 25, 2018|publisher=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> Changes were made to the role of [[superdelegate]]s, deciding to only allow them to vote on the first ballot if the nomination is uncontested<ref name=\"superdelegates\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2018/03/10/dnc-advances-changes-presidential-nominating-process/413876002/|title=DNC advances changes to presidential nominating process|work=USA TODAY|access-date=August 11, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''November 6''': In the [[2018 United States elections|midterm elections]], the Democrats capture control of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] with a net gain of 41 seats. The Republicans hold their majority in the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] with a net gain of two seats.<ref name=\"skelleysenate\">{{cite news |last=Skelley |first=Geoffrey |title=Why Did The House Get Bluer And The Senate Get Redder? |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-did-the-house-get-bluer-and-the-senate-get-redder/ |accessdate=November 16, 2018 |publisher=FiveThirtyEight |date=November 16, 2018}}</ref>     \n*'''November 7''': President Trump confirms that [[Mike Pence]] will remain vice presidential pick<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-election-pence-idUSKCN1NC2HU|title=Trump says Pence to be his running mate in 2020|date=November 7, 2018|work=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n*'''November 11''': West Virginia state senator [[Richard Ojeda]] announces candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party. He ultimately would become the first candidate to withdraw from the race, suspending his campaign on January 25, 2019, more than a year before the Iowa caucus ''(see below)''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsaz.com/content/news/State-Senator-Richard-Ojeda-to-run-for-President-in-2020-500248782.html |title=State Senator Richard Ojeda to run for President in 2020 |author=WSAZ News Staff |date=November 11, 2018 |publisher=[[WSAZ-TV]] |location=Huntington, West Virginia |access-date=December 5, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''December 12''': Former secretary of housing and urban development [[Julian Castro]] forms a presidential exploratory committee for a possible run for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-12-12/urgent-apnewsbreak-julian-castro-moves-toward-2020-white-house-run|title=Julian Castro Forming Presidential Exploratory Committee|last=Weber|first=Paul|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=December 12, 2018|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n*'''December 31''': Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] of Massachusetts forms an exploratory committee for a possible run for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/12/31/politics/elizabeth-warren-exploratory-committee-2020/index.html |title=Elizabeth Warren launches exploratory committee ahead of likely 2020 presidential run |first1=MJ |last1=Lee |first2=Gregory |last2=Krieg |date=December 31, 2018 |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=December 31, 2018}}</ref> She would ultimately decide to commit to an official campaign in February 2019 ''(see below)''.\n\n== 2019 ==\n=== January 2019 ===\n[[File:Kamala Harris announcing her candidacy for presidency.png|thumb|[[Kamala Harris]] launched her campaign on January 21, 2019]]\n\n*'''January 11''': Representative [[Tulsi Gabbard]] of Hawaii announces she has decided to run for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/11/politics/tulsi-gabbard-van-jones/index.html|title=Tulsi Gabbard says she will run for president in 2020|last=Kelly|first=Caroline|date=January 11, 2019|website=Cnn.com|language=en-US|access-date=January 11, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''January 12''': Former [[Secretary of Housing and Urban Development|secretary of housing and urban development]] [[Julian Castro]] officially announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref name=\"bloomberg\" /><ref>{{Citation|last=NBC News|title=Watch Live: Juli\u00e1n Castro to make 2020 presidential campaign announcement|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cECfx0xrPwU|access-date=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''January 15''': Senator [[Kirsten Gillibrand]] of New York announces the formation of an exploratory committee for a possible run for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/15/us/politics/gillibrand-president-election.html|title=Kirsten Gillibrand, New York Senator, Joins Democratic Race for President|last=Goldmacher|first=Shane|date=January 15, 2019|website=Nytimes.com}}</ref> She would then launch an official campaign in March ''(see below)''.\n*'''January 21''': Senator [[Kamala Harris]] of California officially announces her candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref name=\"harris announcement\">{{cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/beta-story-container/Politics/sen-kamala-harris-announces-run-president-2020/story?id=60472358|title=Sen. Kamala Harris announces she will run for president in 2020|date=January 21, 2019|first=Adam|last=Kelsey|work=[[ABC News]]}}</ref>\n*'''January 23''': [[List of mayors of South Bend, Indiana|Mayor]] of [[South Bend, Indiana]], [[Pete Buttigieg]] announces the formation of an exploratory committee for a possible run for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref name=\"Buttigieg-exploratory\">{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/beta-story-container/Politics/south-bend-mayor-pete-buttigieg-announces-presidential-exploratory/story?id=60543998|title=South Bend Mayor Pete Buttigieg launches presidential exploratory committee, could be nation's first openly gay nominee|work=[[ABC News]]|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref>\n*'''January 25''':\n** Ojeda drops out of the Democratic nomination race, saying that he has little chance of success.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Rodrigo|first=Chris|title=Dem Richard Ojeda drops out of presidential race|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/427009-ojeda-drops-out-of-presidential-race|date=January 25, 2019|accessdate=January 25, 2019|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]}}</ref>\n** The [[Republican National Committee]] unofficially endorses Trump.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/republican-party-to-express-undivided-support-for-trump/4756108.html|title=Republican Party to Express 'Undivided Support' for Trump|website=VOA}}</ref>\n*'''January 27:''' [[Starbucks]] founder [[Howard Schultz]] announces possible independent presidential bid,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/democrats-are-uneasy-howard-schultzs-potential-presidential-bid-1179776|title=Former Starbucks Chairman Howard Schultz Announces Potential Presidential Bid on '60 Minutes'|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> which is followed by a furious backlash on social media<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eater.com/2019/1/28/18201052/howard-schultz-president-2020-independent-candidate|title=Running Starbucks Doesn\u2019t Mean You Should Run for President|first=Whitney|last=Filloon|date=January 28, 2019|website=Eater.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2019/01/howard-schultz-backlash-presidential-campaign/|title=Howard Schultz tried to deflect criticism of his presidential flirtation. He only made things worse.|website=Motherjones.com}}</ref>\n*'''January 28''': Spiritual teacher and author [[Marianne Williamson]] of California announces her candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/margiewarrell/2019/01/29/marianne-williamson-can-love-transcend-fear/#3d1050ea141b|title=Marianne Williamson: Can A Presidential Bid Fueled By Love Transcend The Politics Of Fear?|last=Warrell|first=Margie|date=January 29, 2019|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=January 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== February 2019 ===\n[[File:Bill Weld announcing (02).png|thumb|[[Bill Weld]] announcing the formation of an exploratory committee on February 15, 2019, becoming Trump's first official Republican challenger]]\n\n*'''February 1:''' On [[Twitter]], Senator [[Cory Booker]] of New Jersey announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/sen-cory-booker-of-new-jersey-launches-presidential-campaign-11549022453|title=Sen. Cory Booker of New Jersey Launches Presidential Campaign|first=Ken|last=Thomas|date=February 1, 2019|accessdate=February 1, 2019|website=Wsj.com}}</ref>\n*'''February 9''': Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] of Massachusetts announces her candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party, soon after forming an exploratory committee.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-elizabeth-warren-20190209-story.html|title=Elizabeth Warren officially kicks off bid for White House|agency=Associated Press|access-date=February 9, 2019|date=February 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''February 10:''' Senator [[Amy Klobuchar]] of Minnesota announces her candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref name=\"klobuchar announcement\">{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/2/10/18136170/amy-klobuchar-running-president-announcement|title=Sen. Amy Klobuchar has won every one of her elections by huge margins. Now she\u2019s running for president.|first=Tara|last=Golshan|publisher=Vox}}</ref>\n*'''February 12:''' The first mass-rally of the Trump campaign of the year takes place in [[El Paso]], Texas. A counter-rally led by former Democratic U.S. representative [[Beto O'Rourke]] of Texas takes place less than a mile away.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/12/politics/donald-trump-el-paso-beto-orourke/index.html|title=The 50 most eye-popping lines from Donald Trump's El Paso speech|first=Chris|last=Cillizza|website=Cnn.com}}</ref> O\u2019Rourke would later enter the race in March for the Democratic nomination ''(see below)''.\n* '''February 13\u201315:''' Winter meeting of the Democratic National Committee, in which the rules of the upcoming primary are promulgated<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2019-02-13/dnc-chair-2-stages-16-spots-for-first-2-democratic-debates|title=DNC Chair: Qualifications for First Debates Coming This Week|website=Usnews.com|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n*'''February 15:''' Former Massachusetts governor [[Bill Weld]] announces the formation of an exploratory committee, becoming Trump's first official challenger in the Republican primaries<ref>Battenfeld, Joe (February 15, 2019) [https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/02/15/bill-weld-launches-gop-presidential-exploratory-committee/ \"Bill Weld launches GOP presidential exploratory committee\"], ''[[Boston Herald]]''. Retrieved February 15, 2019.</ref>\n*'''February 18:''' [[Youngstown City School District|Youngstown Board of Education]] member [[Dario Hunter]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Green Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wfmj.com/story/39984258/youngstown-board-of-education-member-announces-2020-run|title=Youngstown Board of Education member announces 2020 run|date=February 19, 2019|accessdate=October 6, 2019|author=Koziol, Brandon|work=[[WFMJ-TV]]}}</ref>\n*'''February 19:''' Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] of Vermont announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bing.com/amp/s/www.usnews.com%2fnews%2fnational-news%2farticles%2f2019-02-19%2fbernie-sanders-announces-hes-running-for-president-again-in-2020%3fcontext%3damp|title=Bernie Sanders Is Running for President Again|first=Megan|last=Trimble|date=February 19, 2019|accessdate=February 19, 2019|website=Usnews.com}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2019===\n[[File:Anand Giridharadas interviews Elizabeth Warren 1, SXSW, Austin, Texas, USA (47286394562).jpg|thumb|[[Elizabeth Warren]] (right) being interviewed by [[Anand Giridharadas]] at [[South by Southwest]], March 2019]]\n\n*'''March 1''': Governor [[Jay Inslee]] of [[Washington (state)|Washington]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/01/politics/inslee-2020-presidential-campaign/index.html|title=Washington Gov. Jay Inslee announces 2020 presidential bid|agency=CNN|access-date=March 1, 2019|date=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 4''': Former governor [[John Hickenlooper]] of [[Colorado]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/04/us/john-hickenlooper-2020.html|title=John Hickenlooper Says He Is Running in 2020, Citing a 'Crisis of Division'|agency=New York Times|access-date=March 4, 2019|date=March 4, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 5''': Former mayor [[Michael Bloomberg]] of [[New York City]] announces that, after exploring the possibility, he will not run for president in 2020<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/05/us/politics/michael-bloomberg-2020.html|title=Michael Bloomberg Will Not Run for President in 2020|agency=New York Times|access-date=March 5, 2019|date=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 10:''' Presidential Forum at [[South by Southwest]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://politi.co/2J2HOWj|title=Politico Playbook: 2020 presidential hopefuls gather at SXSW in Austin|first1=Anna|last1=Palmer|first2=Jake|last2=Sherman|first3=Daniel|last3=Lippman|website=Politi.co|accessdate=March 14, 2019}}</ref> the first so-called \"cattle call\" event of the cycle.\n*'''March 11''': [[Milwaukee|Milwaukee, Wisconsin]] is chosen as the host city of the [[2020 Democratic National Convention]], beating out [[Miami, Florida]] and [[Houston|Houston, Texas]].<ref name=\"ABC20190311\">{{cite news | title=Milwaukee chosen as 2020 Democratic National Convention site | url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/milwaukee-chosen-2020-democratic-national-convention-site/story?id=61606127 | first=John | last=Verhovek | publisher=ABC News | date=March 11, 2019 | accessdate=March 11, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 13:''' [[Wayne Messam]], the Democratic mayor of [[Miramar, Florida]], announces the formation of an exploratory committee<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/433890-democratic-florida-mayor-launching-2020-presidential-exploratory-committee|title=Democratic Florida mayor launching 2020 presidential exploratory committee|first=Michael|last=Burke|date=March 13, 2019|website=Thehill.com|accessdate=March 14, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 14:''' O'Rourke officially announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/politics/beto-orourke-running-president-2020/|title=Beto O\u2019Rourke Confirms He\u2019s Running for President in 2020: 'This Is a Defining Moment of Truth'|website=People.com|accessdate=March 14, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 17:''' Gillibrand officially announces her candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/17/us/politics/gillibrand-2020-announce.html|title=Kirsten Gillibrand Officially Enters 2020 Democratic Race|first=Shane|last=Goldmacher|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 17, 2019}}</ref> having previously formed an exploratory committee two month earlier ''(see above)''.\n*'''March 28''': Messam formally announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Merica|first1=Dan|title=Florida Mayor Wayne Messam announces 2020 presidential bid|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/28/politics/wayne-messam-announces-2020-bid/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=March 28, 2019|accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''March 30''': Castro, Delaney, Klobuchar, Ryan, and Warren appear at the Heartland Forum at [[Buena Vista University]] in [[Storm Lake, Iowa]], discussing issues affecting rural Americans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/elizabeth-warren-big-tech-807109/|title=Facebook, Amazon and Google Have a 2020 Problem|last=Kroll|first=Andy|date=March 12, 2019|website=Rolling Stone|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190318233953/https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/elizabeth-warren-big-tech-807109/|archive-date=March 18, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto20\">{{cite web|url=https://iowafarmersunion.org/heartland-forum/|title=Heartland Forum|publisher=Iowa Farmers Union|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326132245/https://iowafarmersunion.org/heartland-forum/|archive-date=March 26, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2019 ===\n[[File:Joe Biden kickoff rally May 2019.jpg|thumb|[[Joe Biden]] launched his campaign on April 25, 2019, increasing the number of major Democratic candidates to 20<ref name=\"BidenCandidacy\"/>]]\n\n* '''April 1''':  Eight Democratic candidates attend the We the People Membership Summit at the [[Warner Theatre (Washington, D.C.)|Warner Theatre]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], discussing [[Electoral reform|Democracy reform]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/20/politics/progressive-summit-2020/index.html|title=Progressive groups to host April summit with 2020 candidates|last=Saenz|first=Arlette|access-date=March 26, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320215117/https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/20/politics/progressive-summit-2020/index.html|archive-date=March 20, 2019|url-status=live|publisher=CNN}}</ref><ref name=\"auto18\">{{cite web|url=https://wethepeople2019.org/|title=We The People Membership Summit 2019|website=Wethepeople2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427140155/https://wethepeople2019.org/|archive-date=April 27, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=April 24, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''April 3\u20135:''' [[National Action Network]] convention. The second so-called \"cattle call\" event of the campaign. Twelve candidates show up and speak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nationalactionnetwork.net/newnews/2019-national-convention-agenda/|title=\u00bb NAN Convention Schedule 2019|website=nationalactionnetwork.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/presidential-candidates-resonate-black-voters-national-action-network/story?id=62138159|title=Presidential candidates try to resonate with black voters at the National Action Network Convention|date=April 5, 2019|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n*'''April 4''': Representative [[Tim Ryan (Ohio politician)|Tim Ryan]] of Ohio announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/ohio-rep-tim-ryan-throws-his-name-growing-2020-field-n990841|title=Ohio Rep. Tim Ryan throws his name into growing 2020 field|date=April 4, 2019|publisher=[[NBC]]|author=Ali Vitali}}</ref>\n*'''April 8''':\n**Senator [[Mike Gravel]] of Alaska announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MikeGravel/status/1115298261215014912|title=\"I'm Mike Gravel, and I'm running for President.\" Together, we are the #Gravelanche. Get Mike to the debates and get this trending! Welcome to the #Gravelanche.|last=Gravel|first=Mike|date=2019-04-08|website=@MikeGravel|language=en|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>\n**Representative [[Eric Swalwell]] of California announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tolan|first1=Casey|title=Eric Swalwell jumps into presidential race with long-shot White House bid|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/04/08/eric-swalwell-presidential-announcement-california/|newspaper=The Mercury News|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''April 14''': Buttigieg officially announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/mayor-presidential-contender-pete-buttigieg-officially-enter-2020/story?id=62345455|title=Pete Buttigieg, little-known mayor turned presidential contender, makes historic bid|last1=Karson|last2=Gomez|first1=Kendall|first2=Justin|date=April 14, 2019|work=[[ABC News]]|accessdate=April 14, 2019}}</ref> having previously formed an exploratory committee earlier in January ''(see above)''.\n*'''April 15''': Weld officially announces his candidacy for the Republican Party nomination,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/15/politics/bill-weld-2020-trump/|title=Bill Weld officially announces he is challenging Trump for GOP nomination in 2020|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=April 15, 2019}}</ref> having previously formed an exploratory committee earlier in February ''(see above)''.\n*'''April 22''': Representative [[Seth Moulton]] of Massachusetts announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/rep-seth-moulton-latest-democrat-enter-2020-field-n996881|title=Rep. Seth Moulton is latest Democrat to enter 2020 field|date=April 22, 2019|access-date=April 22, 2019|last=Seitz-Wald|first=Alex|work=[[NBC News]]}}</ref>\n* '''April 24''': Eight Democratic candidates attend the She the People Presidential Forum at [[Texas Southern University]] in [[Houston|Houston, Texas]], discussing issues affecting women of color.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/first-ever-forum-women-color-presidential-contenders-n987181|title=First-ever forum on women of color for presidential contenders|publisher=NBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327020324/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/first-ever-forum-women-color-presidential-contenders-n987181|archive-date=March 27, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto17\">{{cite web|url=https://www.shethepeople.org/savethedate|title=Save The Date - Presidential Forum|website=She the People|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190326211924/https://www.shethepeople.org/savethedate|archive-date=March 26, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''April 25''': Former vice president [[Joe Biden]] announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination. He becomes the 20th [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries#Declared candidates|major Democratic candidate]] to enter the race.<ref name=\"BidenCandidacy\">{{cite web |last1=Burns |first1=Alexander |title=Joe Biden Is Running for President, After Months of Hesitation |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/25/us/politics/joe-biden-2020.html |website=The New York Times |date=April 25, 2019 | accessdate=April 25, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''April 27''': Several Democratic candidates attend the National Forum on Wages and Working People at Enclave in [[Las Vegas|Las Vegas, Nevada]], discussing economic issues affecting low-income Americans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/top-2020-democrats-booked-las-vegas-labor-forum-april-n987686|title=Top 2020 Democrats booked for Las Vegas labor forum in April|publisher=NBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328032459/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/top-2020-democrats-booked-las-vegas-labor-forum-april-n987686|archive-date=March 28, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto24\">{{cite web|url=https://www.workersforum.org/|title=National Forum on Wages and Working People: Creating an Economy that Works for All|publisher=[[Center for American Progress|CAPAF]] and [[SEIU]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424203122/https://www.workersforum.org/|archive-date=April 24, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=April 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== May 2019 ===\n[[File:Beto O'Rourke (48006058187).jpg|thumb|[[Beto O'Rourke]] speaking at the 2019 California State Democratic Convention, held from May&nbsp;31 to June&nbsp;2]]\n\n*'''May 2''': Senator [[Michael Bennet]] of Colorado announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gregorian |first1=Dareh |title=Colorado Sen. Bennet enters presidential race after prostate cancer treatment |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/colorado-sen-bennet-enters-presidential-race-after-prostate-cancer-treatment-n1000971 |website=NBC News |accessdate=May 2, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n*'''May 14''': Governor [[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Steve Bullock]] of Montana announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/14/us/politics/steve-bullock-2020.html|title=Steve Bullock, Montana Governor, Is Running for President|last=Martin|first=Jonathan|date=2019-05-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n*'''May 16''': \n** New York City Mayor [[Bill de Blasio]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref name=\"DeBlasioPreAnnouncement\">{{cite news|title=New York City Mayor Bill de Blasio to announce his 2020 presidential bid |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/york-city-mayor-bill-de-blasio-announce-2020/story?id=63007952|publisher=ABC News|author=Beatrice Peterson, Zohreen Shah and Justin Gomez|date=May 15, 2019|accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref>\n** Businessman and perennial candidate [[Rocky De La Fuente]] announces his candidacy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Roque_De_La_Fuente_presidential_campaign,_2020|title=Rocky De La Fuente presidential campaign, 2020|publisher=Ballotpedia}}</ref>\n* '''May 28''': Green Party co-founder and perennial candidate [[Howie Hawkins]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Green Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesunion.com/news/article/Howie-Hawkins-will-seek-Green-nomination-for-13900737.php|title=Howie Hawkins will seek Green nomination for president|date=May 28, 2019|accessdate=October 6, 2019|work=[[Times Union (Albany)|Times Union]]}}</ref>\n* '''May 31''': Castro, Inslee, Harris, and Sanders discuss immigration reform at the Unity and Freedom Forum at the Hilton Pasadena, in [[Pasadena, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2019/05/31/bernie-sanders-blasts-trump-as-racist-over-immigration-in-california/1306282001/|title=Bernie Sanders blasts Trump as 'racist' at forum on immigration|work=USA Today|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190601032804/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2019/05/31/bernie-sanders-blasts-trump-as-racist-over-immigration-in-california/1306282001/|archive-date=June 1, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto19\">{{cite web|url=https://firmaction.org/presidentialforum|title=Unity & Freedom Presidential Forum|website=FIRM Action|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604001406/https://firmaction.org/presidentialforum|archive-date=June 4, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''May 31-June 2:''' California State Democratic Convention, a major \"cattle call\" event attended by most major candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cadem.org/events/2019-california-democratic-party-state-convention-may-31-june-2-2019|title=2019 California Democratic Party State Convention, May 31 - June 2, 2019|website=California Democratic Party}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-2020-democratic-candidates-president-california-party-convention-20190603-story.html|title=14 Democratic presidential candidates give California its Cinderella moment|first=Mark Z.|last=Barabak|first2=Melanie|last2=Mason|website=latimes.com}}</ref> Joe Biden is a no-show at the event, attending a [[Human Rights Campaign]] event in Ohio at the same time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/03/politics/2020-democrats-california-progressives-joe-biden/index.html|title=Joe Biden's rift with progressives on display as he skips California Democratic convention|first=Eric|last=Bradner|website=CNN}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://politi.co/2I5MGYk|title=Biden gambles on high-risk primary strategy|first1=Natasha|last1=Korecki|first2=Marc|last2=Caputo|website=POLITICO}}</ref>\n\n=== June 2019 ===\n[[File:Trump Keep America Great 2020 in Orlando.jpg|thumb|[[Donald Trump]] officially kicking-off his re-election campaign in Orlando, Florida on June 18, 2019]]\n\n*'''June 1''': Several Democratic candidates attend the Big Ideas Forum at [[Warfield Theatre]] in [[San Francisco, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/09/moveon-democratic-candidate-forum-1313150|title=MoveOn to host Democratic candidate forum in June|date=May 9, 2019|website=Politico|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509143816/https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/09/moveon-democratic-candidate-forum-1313150|archive-date=May 9, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=May 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''June 5:''' Iowa Democrats' Hall of Fame Dinner: an event featuring 19 candidates. Due to his granddaughter's high school graduation, Biden is absent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2019/06/09/watch_live_19_democratic_presidential_candidates_speak_in_iowa.html|title=19 Democratic Presidential Candidates Speak At Iowa Dinner|first1=Tim|last1=Hains|date=June 9, 2019|website=www.realclearpolitics.com}}</ref>\n*'''June 13:''' The Democratic National Committee announces that 20 candidates will participate in the first official [[2020 Democratic Party presidential debates and forums|Democratic debate]] on June 26\u201327.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/dnc-names-20-candidates-who-will-appear-stage-first-democratic-n1017316|title=DNC names 20 candidates who will appear on stage for first Democratic debate|first=Adam|last=Edelman|work=[[NBC News]]|date=June 13, 2019|accessdate=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''June 15''': Several Democratic candidates attend the Presidential Candidates Forum at Charleston Music Hall in [[Charleston, South Carolina]], televised on a tape delay on [[BET]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/politics/democratic-presidential-candidate-forum-announced-for-charleston-in-june-on/article_0c9a1508-6b6d-11e9-9896-07a5f77c37f2.html|title=Democratic presidential candidate forum announced for Charleston in June on BET|website=[[The Post and Courier]]|access-date=May 13, 2019|date=May 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513182652/https://www.postandcourier.com/politics/democratic-presidential-candidate-forum-announced-for-charleston-in-june-on/article_0c9a1508-6b6d-11e9-9896-07a5f77c37f2.html|archive-date=May 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blackeconomicalliance.org/events/presidential-candidates-forum/|title=Presidential Candidates Forum|publisher=Black Economic Alliance|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609005211/https://blackeconomicalliance.org/events/presidential-candidates-forum/|archive-date=June 9, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 8, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''June 17''': Ten Democratic candidates discuss issues affecting low-income Americans at the Poor People's Campaign Presidential Forum at [[Trinity Washington University]] in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/2020-candidates-to-face-questions-from-low-income-americans-at-forum-poor-peoples-campaign/|title=2020 candidates to face questions from low-income Americans at forum|publisher=CBS News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616015548/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/2020-candidates-to-face-questions-from-low-income-americans-at-forum-poor-peoples-campaign/|archive-date=June 16, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 15, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto23\">{{cite web|url=https://www.poorpeoplescampaign.org/tickets/|title=The Poor People\u2019s Moral Action Congress|publisher=Poor People's Campaign: A National Call for a Moral Revival|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616025214/https://www.poorpeoplescampaign.org/tickets/|archive-date=June 16, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''June 18:''' Trump holds \"kickoff\" rally in [[Orlando]], Florida.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/card/trump-announces-campaign-kickoff-rally-n1012656|title=Trump announces campaign kickoff rally|first=Monica|last=Alba|website=NBC News|accessdate=June 18, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''June 21''': Issues affecting Hispanic and Latino Americans are discussed by eight Democratic candidates at the NALEO Presidential Candidate Forum at [[Telemundo|Telemundo Center]] in [[Miami, Florida]].<ref name=\"auto25\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/democrats-take-their-message-latinos-political-conference-n1020346|title=Democrats take their message to Latinos at political conference|publisher=NBC News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622020536/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/democrats-take-their-message-latinos-political-conference-n1020346|archive-date=June 22, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/naleo/pages/134/attachments/original/1560366826/6_6_19_-_NALEO_Release_-_Presidential_Forum_-_Sanders_and_Buttigieg_-_FINAL.pdf?1560366826|title=U.S. Senator Bernie Sanders and Mayor Pete Buttigieg to Attend NALEO Presidential Candidate Forum at Telemundo Center in Miami|website=NALEO|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623031543/https://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/naleo/pages/134/attachments/original/1560366826/6_6_19_-_NALEO_Release_-_Presidential_Forum_-_Sanders_and_Buttigieg_-_FINAL.pdf?1560366826|archive-date=June 23, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 23, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''June 22''':\n** Democratic candidates make seven-minute speeches at the [[South Carolina Democratic Party]] Convention at the Columbia Convention Center in [[Columbia, South Carolina]].<ref name=\"SCDemcon\">{{Cite web|url=https://scdemweekend.com/|title=2019 South Carolina Democratic Weekend|access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/democratic-candidates-make-nice-try-to-stand-out-in-south-carolina-convention/2019/06/22/0a2c5602-943d-11e9-aadb-74e6b2b46f6a_story.html|title=Democratic candidates make nice, try to stand out in South Carolina convention|last=Janes|first=Chelsea|date=June 22, 2019|work=The Washington Post|access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n** Several Democratic candidates discuss abortion and reproductive health care issues at The We Decide: 2020 Election Membership Forum at the [[University of South Carolina]] in [[Columbia, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/us/politics/planned-parenthood-2020-democrats.html|title=Planned Parenthood to Host Women\u2019s Health Forum for 2020 Democrats|website=The New York Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612155612/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/12/us/politics/planned-parenthood-2020-democrats.html|archive-date=June 12, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 15, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto26\">{{cite web|url=https://www.plannedparenthoodaction.org/pressroom/we-decide-planned-parenthood-action-fund-2020-election-membership-forum-to-focus-on-abortion-and-reproductive-rights|title=We Decide: Planned Parenthood Action Fund 2020 Election Membership Forum to Focus on Abortion and Reproductive Rights|publisher=Planned Parenthood Action Fund|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616035351/https://www.plannedparenthoodaction.org/pressroom/we-decide-planned-parenthood-action-fund-2020-election-membership-forum-to-focus-on-abortion-and-reproductive-rights|archive-date=June 16, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''June 23:''' Former representative [[Joe Sestak]] of Pennsylvania announces his candidacy for the Democratic Party nomination.<ref name=\"Sestak\">{{cite news|last1=Olson|first1=Laura|title=Former Pennsylvania Congressman Joe Sestak announces presidential bid|url=https://www.mcall.com/news/pennsylvania/capitol-ideas/mc-nws-pa-joe-sestak-announces-run-for-president-20190623-bmsevkhpizcyril3jbfclqhk7a-story.html|newspaper=The Morning Call|date=June 23, 2019|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref> Sestak cited his daughter's fight with brain cancer as his reason for his delayed June announcement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Judd|first1=Donald|title=Former Pennsylvania Democratic Rep. Joe Sestak declares run for president in surprise announcement|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/23/politics/joe-sestak-president-campaign/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=June 23, 2019|accessdate=June 23, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''June 26\u201327:''' The Democratic debate series commences with a two-night debate at the [[Adrienne Arsht Center]] in downtown [[Miami]], hosted by NBC and broadcast on its networks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Johnson |first1=Ted |title=DNC Announces Plan for 12 Presidential Primary Debates; First Slated for June |url=https://variety.com/2018/politics/news/dnc-2020-presidential-debates-schedule-1203094098/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety.com]] |accessdate=December 20, 2018 |date=December 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/nbc-news-first-democratic-debate-set-miami-june-26-27-n988481|title=NBC News: First Democratic debate set for Miami, June 26\u201327|website=NBC News|author=Allan Smith|date=March 28, 2019|accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''June 30''': New Hampshire state representative [[Max Abramson]] announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Libertarian Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxabramson.org/home/june-30th-2019|title=\nREP. MAX ABRAMSON ANNOUNCES PRESIDENTIAL BID--BRING THE TROOPS HOME|date=June 30, 2019|accessdate=October 6, 2019|author=Abramson, Max}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seacoastonline.com/news/20190728/seabrooks-abramson-seeks-libertarian-presidential-nomination|title=Seabrook\u2019s Abramson seeks Libertarian presidential nomination|date=July 28, 2019|accessdate=October 6, 2019|author=Sullivan, Max|work=[[The Portsmouth Herald]]}}</ref>\n\n=== July 2019===\n[[File:Bernie Sanders (48235456926).jpg|thumb|[[Bernie Sanders]] campaigning at the [[Ames, Iowa]] July 4 parade, 2019]]\n\n*'''July 5''': Issues affecting public schools are discussed by Democratic candidates at the Strong Public Schools Presidential Forum at the [[George R. Brown Convention Center]] in [[Houston, Texas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/06/14/teachers-union-rolls-out-plans-for-2020-forum-in-houston-1365388|title=Teachers union rolls out plans for 2020 forum in Houston|last=Gaudiano|first=Nicole|date=June 14, 2019|work=[[Politico]]|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto21\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nea.org/home/75033.htm|title=NEA Announces #StrongPublicSchools Presidential Forum|publisher=National Education Association|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616041312/http://www.nea.org/home/75033.htm|archive-date=June 16, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=June 15, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''July 8:''' Swalwell becomes the second candidate, after Ojeda on January 25, to drop out of the Democratic nomination race. Swalwell says that he wanted to narrow the crowded Democratic field after he felt that he did not have a path to winning it himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/08/politics/eric-swalwell-ends-campaign/index.html|title=Eric Swalwell ends presidential bid after failing to gain traction|author1==Rebecca Buck |author2=Dan Merica |author3=Kate Sullivan|website=CNN|access-date=2019-07-09}}</ref>\n*'''July 9:''' Hedge fund manager [[Tom Steyer]] of California announces his candidacy for the nomination of the Democratic Party.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Burns |first1=Alexander |title=Tom Steyer Will Run for President and Plans to Spend $100 Million on His Bid |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/09/us/politics/tom-steyer-president.html |accessdate=July 9, 2019 |issue=July 9, 2019 |publisher=The New York Times}}</ref>\n*'''July 11''': Issues affecting Hispanic and Latino Americans are discussed by Democratic candidates at the League of United Latin American Citizens (LULAC) Presidential Candidates Forum at the [[Wisconsin Center]] in [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"lulac\">{{cite web |title=LULAC Presidential Town Hall |url=https://lulac.org/convention19/lulac_presidential_town_hall_closed/ |publisher=League of United Latin American Citizens |accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=LULAC Presidential Candidates Forum |url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?462452-1/democratic-presidential-candidates-speak-league-united-latin-american-citizens-forum |publisher=C-SPAN |accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''July 11\u201313''': Castro, Gillibrand, Inslee, and Warren make appearances at the [[Netroots Nation]] at the [[Pennsylvania Convention Center]] [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]] by the Netroots Foundation.<ref name=\"nrn\">{{cite news |last1=Krieg |first1=Gregory |title=Elizabeth Warren headlines liberal gathering as other top 2020 contenders skip Netroots |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/13/politics/elizabeth-warren-netroots-nation-2019-progressive-convention/index.html |accessdate=July 14, 2019 |issue=July 13, 2019 |publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n*'''July 15\u201320''': Twenty Democratic candidates make appearances at the Iowa Presidential Candidate Forums in [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]], [[Davenport, Iowa|Davenport]], [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa|Cedar Rapids]], [[Sioux City, Iowa|Sioux City]], and [[Council Bluffs, Iowa|Council Bluffs]].<ref name=aarp>{{cite web|url=https://states.aarp.org/iowa/aarp-and-the-des-moines-register-announce-iowa-presidential-candidate-forums|title=Get Tickets \u2013 AARP and The Des Moines Register Iowa Presidential Candidate Forums|work=[[AARP|AARP Iowa]]|accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''July 18:''' [[CNN]] announces the lineup for the second Democratic debate to be held July 30\u201331.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/18/us/politics/next-democratic-debate-cnn.html|title=Here are the lineups for the next Democratic debate|date=July 18, 2019|website=The New York Times|author=Matt Stevens|accessdate=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''July 24''': Ten Democratic candidates appear at the 2020 Presidential Candidates Forum in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]].<ref name=\"naacp\">{{cite web|url=https://naacp.org/candidatesforum/|title=2020 Presidential Candidates Forum|work=[[NAACP]]|accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''July 30:''' Democratic governor [[Gavin Newsom]] of California signs a bill into state law requiring presidential candidates to release their tax returns for the past five years in order to qualify for the California primary ballot. It is intended to force President Trump to reveal his taxes, which he has refused to do since his 2016 campaign. Republicans view this as unconstitutional, claiming that a state cannot mandate additional eligibility requirements for the presidency beyond what is stated in [[Article Two of the United States Constitution#Clause 5: Qualifications for office|Article Two]] of the [[United States Constitution|US Constitution]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/30/politics/california-presidential-tax-returns-trump-2020/index.html | title=California governor signs bill requiring presidential candidates to submit tax returns | publisher=CNN | date=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''July 30\u201331:''' The second Democratic debate commences with a two-night debate at the [[Fox Theatre (Detroit)|Fox Theatre]] in [[Detroit]], airing on CNN.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/02/politics/cnn-2020-democratic-debate-july-detroit/index.html|title=CNN's 2020 Democratic debate set for July 30-31 in Detroit|date=April 2, 2019|website=CNN|author=Devan Cole|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== August 2019===\n[[File:Andrew Yang (48609991976).jpg|thumb|[[Andrew Yang]] at the Presidential Gun Sense Forum on August 10, 2019]]\n\n* '''August 1:''' Gravel becomes the third candidate to drop out of the Democratic nomination race, citing a failure to qualify for either Democratic debates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/long-shot-candidate-mike-gravels-campaign-closing-shop/story?id=64706997|title=Mike Gravel's 2020 campaign is closing up shop|last=ABC|first=Sruthi Palaniappan and Cheyenne Haslett|website=ABC News|accessdate=August 2, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''August 3''': Nineteen Democratic candidates attend the Public Service Forum at the [[University of Nevada, Las Vegas]].<ref name=\"afscme\">{{cite web|url=https://news3lv.com/politics/presidential-candidates-flock-to-las-vegas-for-public-service-forum-campaign-events|title=2020 Public Service Forum|work=[[KSNV]]|accessdate=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''August 5\u20136:''' Lawsuits are filled to challenge California's new law that will prevent President Trump from appearing on the state's primary ballot unless he releases his tax returns. The first lawsuit is filled by the conservative activist group [[Judicial Watch]] on behalf of four California voters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/456250-voters-sue-california-over-tax-return-law-targeting-trump|title=Voters sue California over tax return law targeting Trump|publisher=The Hill|date=August 5, 2019}}</ref> Additional lawsuits are filed on August 6 by the Trump campaign, the Republican National Committee, and the [[California Republican Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/states/california/story/2019/08/06/new-gop-lawsuits-challenge-newsom-on-trump-tax-bill-1132143|title=New GOP lawsuits challenge Newsom on Trump tax bill|publisher=Politico|date=August 6, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''August 8\u201318:''' The [[Iowa State Fair]] takes place, and is attended by at least twenty of the candidates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iowastatefair.org/entertainment/fair-schedule/|title=Fair Schedule|website=Iowa State Fair}}</ref>\n* '''August 10''': Seventeen Democratic candidates discuss gun issues at the Gun Sense Forum in [[Des Moines, Iowa]].<ref name=\"gunsenseforum\">{{cite web|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2019/08/07/gun-mass-shootings-regulation-iowa-el-paso-dayton-policy-presidential-everytown-2020-trump-democrats/1946231001/|title=17 presidential candidates will attend Saturday's gun forum in Des Moines. Here's what to expect.|work=[[Des Moines Register]]|accessdate=August 7, 2019|author=Robin Opsahl}}</ref>\n*'''August 15''': Hickenlooper becomes the fourth candidate to drop out of the Democratic nomination race. His campaign cites low poll numbers, lack of donors, a large turnover of campaign staff in July, and the likelihood of not qualifying for the third Democratic debate in September.<ref>{{cite news|first=Briana|last=Stewart|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/john-hickenlooper-end-2020-white-house-bid/story?id=64974362|title=John Hickenlooper ends 2020 White House bid|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=August 15, 2019}}</ref>\n*''' August 19''': In the [[Iowa State Fair Straw Poll]], Biden edged Warren by 10 votes among Democratic primary candidates, while Trump won at least 96 percent of the vote among Republican primary candidates.<ref>{{cite news | first=Jay | last=Greene | url=https://www.kcrg.com/content/news/Biden-wins-Iowa-State-Fair-straw-poll-554351921.html | title=Biden wins Iowa State Fair straw poll | publisher=KCRG-TV | date=August 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/458087-biden-edges-warren-in-iowa-state-fair-straw-poll|title=Biden edges Warren in Iowa state fair straw poll|publisher=The Hill|date=August 20, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''August 19\u201320''': Democratic candidates discuss issues affecting Native Americans at the Frank LaMere Native American Presidential Forum at Orpheum Theater in [[Sioux City, Iowa]].<ref name=\"siouxnativeforum\">{{cite web|url=https://siouxcityjournal.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/sioux-city-s-orpheum-to-host-presidential-candidate-forum-on/article_e2b1b41c-32f1-524d-8c2e-f840859e4057.html|title=Sioux City's Orpheum to host presidential candidate forum on Native American issues in August|work=[[Sioux City Journal]]|accessdate=August 5, 2019|author1=Mason Dockter}}</ref>\n*''' August 21''': Inslee becomes the fifth candidate to drop out of the Democratic nomination race.<ref name=\"InsleeWithdraw\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/jay-inslee-drops-out-2020-presidential-race-n1045066|title=Jay Inslee drops out of the 2020 presidential race|date=August 21, 2019|accessdate=August 21, 2019|author=Dareh Gregorian|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> Unlikely to qualify for the third Democratic debate in September, he decides to instead run for another term as governor of Washington.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/21/us/politics/jay-inslee-2020-campaign.html|title=Jay Inslee, Dropping Out of 2020 Race, Will Run for Governor Again|date=August 22, 2019|accessdate=August 22, 2019|author=Alexander Burns and Matt Steven|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref>\n*''' August 23''': Moulton becomes the sixth candidate to drop out of the Democratic primary. Never able to gather enough fundraising or to register in the polls, he decides to instead run for another term in the House of Representatives.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/23/politics/seth-moulton-drops-out-2020-race/index.html|title=Seth Moulton to end 2020 presidential election bid|date=August 23, 2019|accessdate=August 23, 2019|author=Dan Merica|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n*'''August 25:''' Former congressman [[Joe Walsh (Illinois politician)|Joe Walsh]] from Illinois announces his candidacy for the Republican Party nomination, becoming Trump's second official primary challenger after Weld.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/exclusive-joe-walsh-announces-republican-primary-challenge-president/story?id=65122073|title='This Week' Exclusive: Joe Walsh announces Republican primary challenge against Trump|date=August 25, 2019|publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n*'''August 28:'''\n** Gillibrand becomes the seventh candidate to drop out of the Democratic primary, citing her inability to qualify for the third Democratic debate in September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/28/gillibrand-exits-presidential-race-1477644|title=Gillibrand exits presidential race|date=August 28, 2019|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n** Only 10 candidates qualify for the third Democratic debate. Both Gabbard and Steyer criticize its stricter polling criteria that led to their disqualification.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/28/september-democratic-debate-one-night-1476645|title=Democratic debate stage to shrink barring last-minute shock|date=August 28, 2019|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n* '''August 31:''' Due to security concerns, the Democratic National Committee orders both the Iowa and Nevada Democratic state parties to scrap their plans for \"virtual caucuses\", which would have allowed those unable to physically attend the [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Iowa]] or [[2020 Nevada Democratic caucuses|Nevada Democratic caucuses]] to participate online or by teleconference.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/30/iowa-dnc-caucus-1479172|title=DNC throws Iowa, Nevada caucuses into confusion|date=August 31, 2019|publisher=Politico}}</ref>\n\n=== September 2019===\n[[File:NH convention 20190907-DSC03495 (48700564848).jpg|thumb|[[Amy Klobuchar]] speaking at the New Hampshire Democratic state convention on September 7, 2019]]\n\n* '''September 4''': [[CNN]] holds and broadcasts a live seven-hour ''Climate Crisis Town Hall'' from [[New York City]] with the 10 candidates who qualified for the third Democratic debate, who appear one-at-a-time for roughly 40 minutes each.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/25/politics/cnn-climate-crisis-town-hall/index.html|title=Climate Change Townhall|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=July 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/27/politics/cnn-climate-crisis-town-hall-democrats/index.html|title=CNN announces details for climate crisis town hall|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=September 4, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''September 6''': Schultz announces that he will instead not seek an independent presidential bid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/09/06/politics/howard-schultz-presidential-campaign-2020/index.html|title=Howard Schultz drops plans to run as independent candidate in 2020|work=CNN|date=September 6, 2019|accessdate=September 6, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''September 7:'''\n** Kansas, Nevada, and South Carolina Republican state committees vote to cancel their respective primary/caucuses. Both of Trump's major challengers, Walsh and Weld, criticize the move.<ref name=\"ap20190907\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/7e04964fc89a4312a6b410096f256add|title=Nevada, SC, Kansas GOP drop presidential nomination votes|first=Meg|last=Kinnard|work=Associated Press|date=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n** Nineteen Democratic candidates appear at the New Hampshire Democratic state convention.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/07/us/politics/democrats-new-hampshire.html|title=Elizabeth Warren Stands Out at New Hampshire Democratic Party Convention|first=Katie|last=Glueck|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''September 8:'''\n** Former South Carolina governor and congressman [[Mark Sanford]] announces his candidacy for the Republican Party nomination, becoming Trump's third official primary challenger.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/08/us/politics/mark-sanford-president.html|title=Mark Sanford Will Challenge Trump in Republican Primary|website=New York Times|date=September 8, 2019}}</ref>\n** Gabbard, Steyer, and Yang attend the Asian American Pacific Islanders Progressive Democratic Presidential Forum at the [[Segerstrom Center for the Arts]] in [[Costa Mesa, California]].<ref name=latsept8>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/socal/daily-pilot/news/story/2019-09-08/three-democratic-presidential-hopefuls-costa-mesa|title=Three Democratic presidential hopefuls state their case at forum in Costa Mesa|last=Zint|first=Bradley|date=September 8, 2019|website=Los Angeles Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''September 9:''' The Arizona Republican Party officially notifies Arizona secretary of state [[Katie Hobbs]] that they will scrap the Arizona Republican primary.<ref name=\"ktar20190909\">{{cite news|url=https://ktar.com/story/2734796/arizona-gop-wont-hold-2020-presidential-preference-election/|title=Arizona GOP won\u2019t hold 2020 presidential preference election|publisher=KTAR|date=September 9, 2019|accessdate=September 12, 2019|author=Kevin Stone}}</ref>\n*'''September 12:''' The third Democratic debate takes place at [[Health and Physical Education Arena|H&PE Arena]] on the campus of [[Texas Southern University]] in [[Houston]], airing on ABC and Univision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialbuzz.com/dnc-raises-requirements-to-qualify-for-third-presidential-debate/ |title=DNC Raises Requirements to Qualify for Third Presidential Debate |last=Shin |first=Bryan |date=May 30, 2019 |work=FinancialBuzz |access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=TSU Selected as Venue for Democratic Primary Debate |url=http://www.tsu.edu/news/2019/07/tsu-venue-for-dem-primary-debate.html|work=[[Texas Southern University]]|date=July 21, 2019 |accessdate=July 22, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''September 17:''' Six Democratic candidates appear at the Workers' Presidential Summit at the [[Pennsylvania Convention Center]] in [[Philadelphia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.phillymag.com/news/2019/09/17/presidential-summit/|title=Biden, Sanders Among 6 Democratic Presidential Candidates in Philly on Tuesday|last=Sasko|first=Claire|date=September 17, 2019|website=Philadelphia Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=September 18, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''September 19\u201320''': A Climate Forum, sponsored by [[MSNBC]], takes place at [[Gaston Hall]] on the campus of [[Georgetown University]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"climateforumdc\">{{Cite web|url=https://thinkprogress.org/democrats-climate-debate-forum-sunrise-movement-dnc-cnn-msnbc-56d099e7748c/|title=In a historic first, two climate forums announced for 2020 Democratic candidates|author=E. A. Crunden|work=[[ThinkProgress]]|date=July 26, 2019|accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/the-energy-202/2019/09/20/the-energy-202-four-big-takeways-from-the-msnbc-climate-change-town-hall/5d83b04b88e0fa0ba8961cad/|title=The Energy 202: Four big takeaways from the MSNBC climate change town hall|newspaper=Washington Post|date=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''September 20:'''\n** de Blasio becomes the eighth candidate to drop out of the Democratic primary, admitting that he had no chance of winning the nomination.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/20/politics/bill-de-blasio-ends-presidential-campaign/index.html|title=De Blasio drops out of 2020 presidential race|publisher=CNN|date=September 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/09/20/bill-de-blasio-ends-2020-presidential-campaign-1506011|title=Bill de Blasio ends 2020 presidential campaign|publisher=Politico|date=September 20, 2019}}</ref>\n** Ten Democratic candidates appear at the LGBTQ Forum on the campus of [[Coe College]] in [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.advocate.com/politics/2019/8/28/2020-presidential-lgbtq-forum-gets-support-glaad-livestream-date|title=2020 Presidential LGBTQ Forum Gets Support From GLAAD, Live Stream|date=August 28, 2019|website=The Advocate}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/identities/2019/9/21/20876742/lgbtq-presidential-forum-winners-losers|title=2 winners and 3 losers from the LGBTQ presidential forum|date=September 20, 2019|website=Vox}}</ref>\n*'''September 21:'''\n** Buttigieg, Castro, Sanders, and Warren appear at the Iowa People's Presidential Forum at the Iowa Events Center in [[Des Moines, Iowa]].<ref name=\"auto29\">{{Cite web|url=https://peoplesaction.org/peoples-presidential-forums/|title=People\u2019s Presidential Forums|date=January 28, 2019|website=People's Action|language=en-US|access-date=July 26, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/elections/presidential/caucus/2019/09/21/iowa-cci-peoples-presidential-forum-bernie-sanders-pete-buttigieg-democrat-socialist-progressive-dsm/2405666001/|title=A warm reception for liberal presidential candidates, lion's den for moderates at CCI forum in Iowa|date=September 21, 2019|newspaper=Des Moines Register}}</ref>\n** The Alaska Republican Party officially scraps its state's Republican primary, stating it \"would serve no useful purpose\" because Trump is the incumbent president.<ref name=\"abc20190921\">{{cite news|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/wireStory/alaska-gop-scraps-2020-presidential-primary-helping-trump-65773870|title=Alaska GOP scraps 2020 presidential primary, helping Trump|work=Associated Press|publisher=ABC News|date=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n*'''September 22:''' Six Democratic candidates appear at the Youth Forum at [[Theodore Roosevelt High School (Des Moines)|Roosevelt High School]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa]].<ref name=\"youthforum1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dmschools.org/news_release/dmps-register-sponsor-youth-voice-forum-presidential-candidates/|title=DMPS, Register Host Youth Forum for Presidential Candidates|date=September 11, 2019|website=Des Moines Public Schools|access-date=September 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* '''September 24:''' \n**[[Nancy Pelosi]], the [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|speaker of the House of Representatives]], announces the start of a formal [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|impeachment inquiry against Trump]].<ref name=\"WashPo 2019-09-24\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com