{"title_page": "Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount Gage", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n'''Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount Gage''' (bef. 1702 \u2013 21 December 1754) of High Meadow, Gloucestershire and later Firle Place, Sussex, was a British landowner and politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] for 33 years between 1717 and 1754.\n\n[[File:1st_Viscount_Gage.jpg|thumb|right|1743 Portrait of Thomas Gage by [[James Seymour]] ]]\n\n==Early life==\nGage was the eldest son of Joseph Gage of [[Sherborne Castle]] and Elizabeth Penruddock, the daughter and heiress of Sir George Penruddock. He succeeded his father-in-law to High Meadow in 1714.  Under a marriage settlement dated 3 October 1713, he married Benedicta Maria Theresa Hall, daughter and heiress of Henry Benedict Hall of High Meadow, Gloucestershire and his wife Frances Fortescue.<ref name=HOP>{{cite web|url=https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/gage-thomas-1695-1754|title=GAGE, Thomas (c.1695-1754), of High Meadow, Glos.|publisher= History of Parliament Trust|accessdate= 27 October 2018}}</ref> He converted to the [[Church of England]] in 1715, perhaps to enable him to sit in parliament.<ref name=\"Alden5_8\">[[#Alden|Alden (1948)]], pp. 5,8</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGage was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for Minehead at a by-election on 11 April 1717, but was unseated on petition on 23 May 1717. On 14 September 1720, [[George I of Great Britain|King George I]] created him '''[[Baron Gage]]''' of [[Castlebar]] in the [[County Mayo|county of Mayo]], and '''[[Viscount Gage]]''' of [[Castleisland|Castle Island]] in the [[County Kerry|county of Kerry]] of the [[Kingdom of Ireland]].<ref name=HOP/>\n          \nGage was elected MP for [[Tewkesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Tewkesbury]] at a by-election on 25 October  1721 and was elected again at the [[1722 British general election|1722 general election]]. In his first session of this parliament, he made several speeches against the special tax on Papists. In April 1727 he spoke for the motion for a vote of credit. He was returned again at the [[1727 British general election|1727 general election]]. He exposed the fraudulent sale of the [[Dilston Castle#The Derwentwater estates after 1716|Derwentwater estates]] on 31 March 1732, and was subsequently rewarded with \u00a32,000 for this under the [[Greenwich Hospital (London)|Greenwich Hospital]] Act 1735.<ref>''Statutes at Large'' (1758 edition) V, 8 Geo. II, c.29.</ref> At the [[1734 British general election|1734 general election]], he was returned again as MP for Tewkesbury. He introduced a bill to prevent clandestine marriages, in 1736, but it was rejected. In 1738, it was rumoured that he was to be appointed as [[Governor of Barbados]], but the appointment was never materialised,<ref name=HOP/> probably because he lacked sufficient political connections.<ref name=\"Alden6\">[[#Alden|Alden (1948)]], p. 6</ref> He went into opposition with Pulteney in 1739, but in February 1741, he was one of the opposition Whigs who withdrew on the motion for Walpole's removal. He was returned to parliament again at the [[1741 British general election|1741 general election]].<ref name=HOP/>\n[[File:Firle Place.jpg|thumb|Firle Place from rear]]\nOn 23 April 1744, his cousin, [[Sir William Gage, 7th Baronet]], died without children, and Gage inherited the baronetcy and the family estate of [[Firle Place]]. Sir William's late father was Gage's uncle - [[Sir John Gage, 4th Baronet]], Sheriff of [[Sussex]]. The main line of the family, up to the 7th Baronet, had been Roman Catholic [[recusant]]s who had purchased their [[baronet]]cy from [[James I of England|King James I]], and  Gage quietly resumed practising Roman Catholicism, although his children were raised in the Church of England. At the [[1747 British general election|1747 general election]], he was returned again for Tewkesbury and joined the opposition. In 1747 was appointed  Steward of the Household of [[Frederick, Prince of Wales]] and held the post until 1751.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==Later life==\nGage's wife died on 25 July 1749, and on 26 December 1750 he married secondly Jane Godfrey, a Gloucestershire heiress.<ref name=\"Alden8\">[[#Alden|Alden (1948)]], p. 8</ref> He had extensive remodelling work done on Firle Place and between 1743 and 1753, and was involved in a number of [[land rights]] disputes regarding windfall trees, soil rights, and manorial waste. Gage also spent considerable time collecting paintings which are still housed in the Long Gallery of Firle Place today.\n\nGage and his son were defeated at the 1754 general election, having decided not to respond to the threats of his voters only to vote for candidates who promised to give \u00a31,500 towards mending the roads.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nGage died on 21 December 1754 and was buried at [[Firle]]. He was succeeded by his eldest son [[William Hall Gage, 2nd Viscount Gage]]. He also had a daughter, Theresa, and a second son [[Thomas Gage]] who went on to fame as [[Commander-in-Chief]] of the [[British Army]] in [[British America]] at the beginning of the [[American War of Independence]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Viscount Gage]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite book|title=General Gage in America|first=John R|last=Alden|location=Baton Rouge, LA|publisher=Louisiana State University Press|year=1948|oclc=181362|isbn=978-0-8371-2264-9|ref=Alden|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/generalgageiname00alde}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[William Dowdeswell (1682\u20131728)|William Dowdeswell (1)]]\n | before2 = [[Nicholas Lechmere, 1st Baron Lechmere|Nicholas Lechmere]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = Member of Parliament for [[Tewkesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Tewkesbury]]\n | years = 1721\u20131754\n | with  = [[William Dowdeswell (1682\u20131728)|William Dowdeswell (1)]] 1721\u20131722\n | with2 = [[George Reade]] 1722\u20131734|with3=[[Robert Tracy (MP)|Robert Tracy]] 1734\u20131741\n | with4 = [[John Martin (1692\u20131767)|John Martin]] 1741\u20131747\n | with5 = [[William Dowdeswell (Chancellor)|William Dowdeswell (2)]] 1747\u20131754\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Nicolson Calvert (died 1793)|Nicolson Calvert]]\n | after2 = [[John Martin (1724\u20131794)|John Martin]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Joseph Micklethwait]]\n | before2 = [[Thomas Lumley]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = Member of Parliament for [[Arundel (UK Parliament constituency)|Arundel]]\n | years = 1727\u20131728\n | with  = [[Sir John Shelley, 4th Baronet|Sir John Shelley, Bt]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir John Shelley, 4th Baronet|Sir John Shelley, Bt]]\n | after2 = [[John Lumley (MP)|John Lumley]]\n}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Governor of Barbados]]|years=1738\u20131739|before=[[Humphrey Howarth]]|after=[[Robert Byng (18th-century MP)|Robert Byng]]}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{s-new}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Viscount Gage]]|years=1720\u20131754}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William Gage, 2nd Viscount Gage|William Hall Gage]]}}\n{{s-reg|en-bt}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sir William Gage, 7th Baronet|William Gage]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Gage baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''(of Firle Place)''' | years=1744\u20131754}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William Gage, 2nd Viscount Gage|William Hall Gage]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gage, Thomas 1st Viscount Gage}}\n[[Category:1700s births|Gage, Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:1754 deaths|Gage, Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Converts to Anglicanism]]\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of Ireland|Gage, Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Peers of Ireland created by George I]]\n[[Category:Governors of Barbados|Gage, Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Gage family]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies|Gage, Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1715\u20131722]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1722\u20131727]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1734\u20131741]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1741\u20131747]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1747\u20131754]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2011}}\n'''Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount Gage''' (bef. 1702 \u2013 21 December 1754) of High Meadow, Gloucestershire and later Firle Place, Sussex, was a British landowner and politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] for 33 years between 1717 and 1754.\n\n[[File:1st_Viscount_Gage.jpg|thumb|right|1743 Portrait of Thomas Gage by [[James Seymour]] ]]\n\n==Early life==\nGage was the eldest son of Joseph Gage of [[Sherborne Castle]] and Elizabeth Penruddock, the daughter and heiress of Sir George Penruddock. He succeeded his father-in-law to High Meadow in 1714.  Under a marriage settlement dated 3 October 1713, he married Benedicta Maria Theresa Hall, daughter and heiress of Henry Benedict Hall of High Meadow, Gloucestershire and his wife Frances Fortescue.<ref name=HOP>{{cite web|url=https://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/gage-thomas-1695-1754|title=GAGE, Thomas (c.1695-1754), of High Meadow, Glos.|publisher= History of Parliament Trust|accessdate= 27 October 2018}}</ref> He converted to the [[Church of England]] in 1715, perhaps to enable him to sit in parliament.<ref name=\"Alden5_8\">[[#Alden|Alden (1948)]], pp. 5,8</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGage was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for Minehead at a by-election on 11 April 1717, but was unseated on petition on 23 May 1717. On 14 September 1720, [[George I of Great Britain|King George I]] created him '''[[Baron Gage]]''' of [[Castlebar]] in the [[County Mayo|county of Mayo]], and '''[[Viscount Gage]]''' of [[Castleisland|Castle Island]] in the [[County Kerry|county of Kerry]] of the [[Kingdom of Ireland]].<ref name=HOP/>\n          \nGage was elected MP for [[Tewkesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Tewkesbury]] at a by-election on 25 October  1721 and was elected again at the [[1722 British general election|1722 general election]]. In his first session of this parliament, he made several speeches against the special tax on Papists. In April 1727 he spoke for the motion for a vote of credit. He was returned again at the [[1727 British general election|1727 general election]]. He exposed the fraudulent sale of the [[Dilston Castle#The Derwentwater estates after 1716|Derwentwater estates]] on 31 March 1732, and was subsequently rewarded with \u00a32,000 for this under the [[Greenwich Hospital (London)|Greenwich Hospital]] Act 1735.<ref>''Statutes at Large'' (1758 edition) V, 8 Geo. II, c.29.</ref> At the [[1734 British general election|1734 general election]], he was returned again as MP for Tewkesbury. He introduced a bill to prevent clandestine marriages, in 1736, but it was rejected. In 1738, it was rumoured that he was to be appointed as [[Governor of Barbados]], but the appointment was never materialised,<ref name=HOP/> probably because he lacked sufficient political connections.<ref name=\"Alden6\">[[#Alden|Alden (1948)]], p. 6</ref> He went into opposition with Pulteney in 1739, but in February 1741, he was one of the opposition Whigs who withdrew on the motion for Walpole\u2019s removal. He was returned to parliament again at the [[1741 British general election|1741 general election]].<ref name=HOP/>\n[[File:Firle Place.jpg|thumb|Firle Place from rear]]\nOn 23 April 1744, his cousin, [[Sir William Gage, 7th Baronet]], died without children, and Gage inherited the baronetcy and the family estate of [[Firle Place]]. Sir William's late father was Gage's uncle - [[Sir John Gage, 4th Baronet]], Sheriff of [[Sussex]]. The main line of the family, up to the 7th Baronet, had been Roman Catholic [[recusant]]s who had purchased their [[baronet]]cy from [[James I of England|King James I]], and  Gage quietly resumed practising Roman Catholicism, although his children were raised in the Church of England. At the [[1747 British general election|1747 general election]], he was returned again for Tewkesbury and joined the opposition. In 1747 was appointed  Steward of the Household of [[Frederick, Prince of Wales]] and held the post until 1751.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==Later life==\nGage's wife died on 25 July 1749, and on 26 December 1750 he married secondly Jane Godfrey, a Gloucestershire heiress.<ref name=\"Alden8\">[[#Alden|Alden (1948)]], p. 8</ref> He had extensive remodelling work done on Firle Place and between 1743 and 1753, and was involved in a number of [[land rights]] disputes regarding windfall trees, soil rights, and manorial waste. Gage also spent considerable time collecting paintings which are still housed in the Long Gallery of Firle Place today.\n\nGage and his son were defeated at the 1754 general election, having decided not to respond to the threats of his voters only to vote for candidates who promised to give \u00a31,500 towards mending the roads.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nGage died on 21 December 1754 and was buried at [[Firle]]. He was succeeded by his eldest son [[William Hall Gage, 2nd Viscount Gage]]. He also had a daughter, Theresa, and a second son [[Thomas Gage]] who went on to fame as [[Commander-in-Chief]] of the [[British Army]] in [[British America]] at the beginning of the [[American War of Independence]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Viscount Gage]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite book|title=General Gage in America|first=John R|last=Alden|location=Baton Rouge, LA|publisher=Louisiana State University Press|year=1948|oclc=181362|isbn=978-0-8371-2264-9|ref=Alden|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/generalgageiname00alde}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[William Dowdeswell (1682\u20131728)|William Dowdeswell (1)]]\n | before2 = [[Nicholas Lechmere, 1st Baron Lechmere|Nicholas Lechmere]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = Member of Parliament for [[Tewkesbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Tewkesbury]]\n | years = 1721\u20131754\n | with  = [[William Dowdeswell (1682\u20131728)|William Dowdeswell (1)]] 1721\u20131722\n | with2 = [[George Reade]] 1722\u20131734|with3=[[Robert Tracy (MP)|Robert Tracy]] 1734\u20131741\n | with4 = [[John Martin (1692\u20131767)|John Martin]] 1741\u20131747\n | with5 = [[William Dowdeswell (Chancellor)|William Dowdeswell (2)]] 1747\u20131754\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Nicolson Calvert (died 1793)|Nicolson Calvert]]\n | after2 = [[John Martin (1724\u20131794)|John Martin]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Joseph Micklethwait]]\n | before2 = [[Thomas Lumley]]\n}}\n{{s-ttl\n | title = Member of Parliament for [[Arundel (UK Parliament constituency)|Arundel]]\n | years = 1727\u20131728\n | with  = [[Sir John Shelley, 4th Baronet|Sir John Shelley, Bt]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Sir John Shelley, 4th Baronet|Sir John Shelley, Bt]]\n | after2 = [[John Lumley (MP)|John Lumley]]\n}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Governor of Barbados]]|years=1738\u20131739|before=[[Humphrey Howarth]]|after=[[Robert Byng (18th-century MP)|Robert Byng]]}}\n{{s-reg|ie}}\n{{s-new}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Viscount Gage]]|years=1720\u20131754}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William Gage, 2nd Viscount Gage|William Hall Gage]]}}\n{{s-reg|en-bt}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sir William Gage, 7th Baronet|William Gage]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Gage baronets|Baronet]]<br />'''(of Firle Place)''' | years=1744\u20131754}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[William Gage, 2nd Viscount Gage|William Hall Gage]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gage, Thomas 1st Viscount Gage}}\n[[Category:1700s births|Gage, Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:1754 deaths|Gage, Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Converts to Anglicanism]]\n[[Category:Viscounts in the Peerage of Ireland|Gage, Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Peers of Ireland created by George I]]\n[[Category:Governors of Barbados|Gage, Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:Gage family]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies|Gage, Thomas Gage, 1st Viscount]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1715\u20131722]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1722\u20131727]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1734\u20131741]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1741\u20131747]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1747\u20131754]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Gage,_1st_Viscount_Gage"}
{"title_page": "McIntosh County Academy", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = January 2020}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name                   = McIntosh County Academy\n|logo                   = \n|seal_image             = \n|image                  = McIntosh County Academy.jpg\n|image_size             =\n|caption                = \n|motto                  = \n|motto_translation      = \n|streetaddress          = 8945 US Highway 17\n|city                   = [[Darien, Georgia|Darien]]\n|state                  = [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n|zipcode                = 31305\n|country                = United States\n|coordinates            = {{Coord|31.440214|-81.431022|display=title,inline|format=dms|type:edu}}\n|schooltype             = [[Secondary school|secondary]]\n|fundingtype            = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]]\n|opened                 = 1875<ref name=\"Lewis, Bessie p.58\">Lewis, Bessie. They Called Their Town Darien p.58. Darien, GA: The Darien News, 1975.</ref>\n|status                 = \n|closed                 =\n|district               = [[McIntosh County School District]]\n|us_nces_district_id    = 1303600<ref name=\"shortlogicalname\">{{Cite web| title = McIntosh County Academy| work = Statistical information| publisher = National Center for Education Statistics (NCES)| date = October 2009| url = http://nces.ed.gov/globallocator/sch_info_popup.asp?Type=Public&ID=130360002413| accessdate = 5 August 2011}}</ref>\n|superintendent         = Minorax is daddy\n|ceeb                   = \n|us_nces_school_id      = 130360002413<ref name=\"shortlogicalname\"/>\n|principal              = Chris Wolski name=\"Staff Directory\">{{Cite web| title = Staff Diretory| publisher = McIntosh County Academy| date = November 2010| url = http://mca.mcintosh.k12.ga.us/?PageName='Teachers'| accessdate = 5 August 2011}}</ref>\n|staff                  = \n|faculty                = \n|teaching_staff         = 37<ref name=\"Staff Directory\">{{Cite web| title = Staff Diretory| publisher = McIntosh County Academy| date = November 2010| url = http://mca.mcintosh.k12.ga.us/?PageName='Teachers'| accessdate = 5 August 2011}}</ref>\n|employees              = \n|grades                 = [[Ninth grade|9]]-[[Twelfth grade|12]]\n|gender                 = [[Mixed-sex education|Coed]]\n|enrollment             = 543<ref name=\"shortlogicalname\"/>\n|enrollment_as_of       = 2009-10\n|avg_class_size         = \n|ratio                  = 15:1<ref name=\"shortlogicalname\"/>\n|campus size            = \n|area                   = \n|campus type            = [[rural#Rural schools|Rural fringe]]<ref name=\"shortlogicalname\"/>\n|campus_Bound           = \n|colors                 = {{Color box|red|border=darkgray}} [[Red (color)|red]]<br>{{Color box|black|border=darkgray}} [[Black|black]]<br>{{Color box|gold|border=darkgray}} [[Gold (color)|gold]]\n|slogan                 = \n|song                   = \n|fightsong              = \n|conference             = \n|mascot                 = \n|mascot image           = \n|team_name              = [[Buccaneers (disambiguation)|Buccaneers]]\n|accreditation          = \n|SAT                    = \n|ACT                    =\n|publication            = \n|newspaper              = \n|yearbook               = \n|nobel_laureates        = \n|free_label             = \n|free_text              = \n|free_label1            = \n|free_text1             = \n|free_label2            = \n|free_text2             = \n|free_label3            = \n|free_text3             = \n|free_label4            = \n|free_text4             = \n|free_label5            = \n|free_text5             = \n|website                = [http://mca.mcintosh.k12.ga.us mca.mcintosh.k12.ga.us]\n|picture                = \n|picture_caption        =  \n|picture2               = \n|picture_caption2       =  \n}}\n'''McIntosh County Academy''' ('''MCA''') is the only public high school in [[McIntosh County, Georgia|McIntosh County]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcintosh.k12.ga.us/|title=McIntosh County Schools > Home|work=mcintosh.k12.ga.us}}</ref> It was formerly known as Darien High School.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Mcintosh_County_Academy_Side.jpg|right|thumb|Side view]]\n\nIn 1794, the city of [[Darien, Georgia|Darien]] was given a charter to build a school.<ref>Coulter, Thomas Spalding of Sapelo p. 189</ref> In 1820, a branch of the institution was created and classes were held at local churches.<ref name=\"Lewis, Bessie p.58\"/> The actual school building was built in 1840 on the corner of Adam Street and Rittenhouse Street.\n\nOn March 3, 1892, an intentional fire destroyed McIntosh County Academy. The city rebuilt a brick building on top of the remains of the old school in the same year.<ref>Sullivan, Buddy. Early Days on the Georgia Tidewater. Darien, GA: The Darien News, 1990.</ref> This was the site of the school for many years, until Darien constructed the new high school off [[U.S. Route 17|U.S Highway 17]].\n\nMCA was built using the one cent ESPLOST (Education Special Local Option Sales Tax).<ref>[http://images.schoolinsites.com/SiSFiles/Schools/GA/McIntoshCounty/McIntoshAcademy/Uploads/DocumentsCategories/Documents/SPLOST%20PhotoStory1.wmv] {{dead link|date=December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Extra-curricular activities==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[4-H]]\n* Beta Club\n* Drama Club\n* [[FBLA]] (Future Business Leaders of America)\n* [[Fellowship of Christian Athletes|FCA]] (Fellowship of Christian Athletes)\n* [[FCCLA]] (Family, Career, Community Leaders of America)\n* [[National FFA Organization|FFA]] (Future Farmers of America)\n* Guitar Club\n* [[HOSA (organization)|HOSA]] (Health Occupations Students of America)\n* Independent Authors\n* Interact Club\n* [[Junior Optimist Octagon International|JOOIC]] (Junior Optimist Octagon International)\n* [[National Honor Society]]\n* Science Club\n* [[SkillsUSA|Skills USA-Vica]]\n* Student Council\n* [[Youth Advisory Council|YAC]] (Youth Advisory Council)\n* Yearbook\n* Gaming club\n{{div col end}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mca.mcintosh.k12.ga.us/?PageName=%27Organizations%27|title=McIntosh County Academy > Home|work=mcintosh.k12.ga.us}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nIn 2005, MCA began offering [[Advanced Placement]] classes in [[Calculus]], English, [[US History]], [[Environmental Science]], and [[Art History]]. These classes are available to juniors and seniors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mca.mcintosh.k12.ga.us/?PageName=LatestNews&Section=LatestNews&ItemID=71188&ISrc=School&Itype=News|title=McIntosh County Academy > Home|work=mcintosh.k12.ga.us}}</ref>\n\nMCA did not make [[Adequate Yearly Progress|AYP]] until 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.education.com/schoolfinder/us/georgia/darien/mcintosh-county-academy/|title=McIntosh County Academy|work=education.com}}</ref>\n\nMCA was first place in the 2007 [[Georgia High School Association|GHSA]] Region 2 [[GHSGT]] in English with a 93.7%. The graduation rate rose to third place among the GHSA boards, with 70.6% graduating.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n* [[Allen Bailey]] - [[NFL]] player, [[Atlanta Falcons]] Class of 2007\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{portal|School|Georgia (U.S. state)}}\n* [http://mca.mcintosh.k12.ga.us Official website]\n* [http://mcintosh.k12.ga.us McIntosh County School system]\n{{GHSA Class AA Region 2}}\n\n[[Category:Public high schools in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Schools in McIntosh County, Georgia]]\n[[Category:1875 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = January 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = January 2020}}\n{{Infobox school\n|name                   = McIntosh County Academy\n|logo                   = \n|seal_image             = \n|image                  = McIntosh County Academy.jpg\n|image_size             =\n|caption                = \n|motto                  = \n|motto_translation    