tps://www.amazon.com/Against-Anti-Americanism-International-Relations-Political/dp/0230602266/  excerpt and text search], essays by scholars in Europe and Asia\n* {{cite book|last=Larson|first=Eric Victor|author2=Levin, Norman D.|author3=Baik, Seonhae|author4=Savych, Bogdan|title=Ambivalent Allies? A Study of South Korean Attitudes toward the U.S.|url=https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=102789791|publisher=Rand|year=2004|isbn=0-8330-3584-3|location=|pages=}}\n* {{cite book|first=Andrei S.|last=Markovits|title=Uncouth Nation: Why Europe Dislikes America|publisher=Princeton UP|year=2007|isbn=0-691-12287-3|location=|pages=|url=https://archive.org/details/uncouthnationwhy00mark}}\n* {{cite book|editor=Nakaya, Andrea C.|title=[[Does the World Hate the United States?]]|last=|first=|publisher=[[Greenhaven Press]]|location=Farmington Hills, Michigan|pages=|year=2005|isbn=}}\n* {{cite journal|first=Brendon|last=O'Connor|title=A Brief History of Anti-Americanism: From Cultural Criticism to Terrorism|url=|journal=Australasian Journal of American Studies|volume=23|issue=1|date=July 2004|page=82|pages=|ref=harv|via=}}\n* {{cite book|editor1-first=Brendon|location=|pages=|editor1-last=O'Connor|editor2-first=Martin|editor2-last=Griffiths|title=The Rise of anti-Americanism|last=|first=|publisher=Routledge|year=2005|isbn=}}\n* {{cite book|editor=O'Connor, Brendon|location=|pages=|title=Anti-Americanism: History, Causes, Themes|last=|first=|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=2007|isbn=1-84645-004-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/antiamericanismh0000unse}}\n* {{cite book|editor=O'Connor, B.|editor2=Griffiths, M. |year=2007 |title=Anti-Americanism: Comparative perspectives |volume=Vol. 3 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing}}\n* {{cite book|last1=O'Connor|first1=Brendon|last2=Griffiths|first2=Martin|title=The rise of anti-Americanism|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lJLIIZN8szYC|year=2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-36906-0|location=|pages=|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Richard|last=Pells|url=https://www.questia.com/PM.qst?a=o&d=8912267|title=Not like Us: How Europeans Have Loved, Hated, and Transformed American Culture since World War II|publisher=Basic Books|location=New York|pages=|year=1997|isbn=}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|last=Revel|authorlink=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Revel|title=Europe's Anti-American Obsession|work=The View from Abroad|publisher=The American Enterprise Institute|url=http://theamericanenterprise.org/issues/articleid.17764/article_detail.asp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031204174924/http://theamericanenterprise.org/issues/articleid.17764/article_detail.asp|archivedate=4 December 2003|year=2003|isbn=|location=|pages=|accessdate=4 December 2003}}\n* {{cite book|first=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois|last=Revel|authorlink=Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Revel|title=Anti-Americanism|url=https://archive.org/details/antiamericanism00reve|url-access=registration|location=San Francisco|pages=|publisher=Encounter Books|isbn=1-59403-060-X|year=2003}}\n* {{cite book|first=Barry|last=Rubin|authorlink=Barry Rubin|author2=Rubin, Judith Colp|title=Hating America: A History|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2004|isbn=0-19-530649-X|location=|pages=}} <!--[http://www.h-net.msu.edu/reviews/showrev.cgi?path=128551165243518 online review]-->\n* Shiraev, Eric, and Vladimir Zubok. (2000) ''Anti\u2010Americanism in Russia: From Stalin to Putin''\n* {{cite book|first=Julia|last=Sweig|url=https://archive.org/details/friendlyfirelosi00swei|title=Friendly Fire: Losing Friends and Making Enemies in the Anti-American Century|publisher=PublicAffairs|year=2006|isbn=1-58648-300-5|access-date=28 March 2006|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}\n* {{cite journal|first=Charles J.|last=Swindells|title=Anti-Americanism and Its Discontents|url=|journal=New Zealand International Review|volume=30|issue=1|date=|year=2005|pages=8+|issn=0110-0262|ref=harv|via=}}\n* {{cite book|first=Frank|last=Trommler|author2=McVeigh, Joseph|title=America and the Germans: An Assessment of a Three-Hundred-Year History|location=|pages=|chapter=Volume 2: The Relationship in the Twentieth Century|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|year=1990|isbn=}}\n* {{cite book|author=Woodward, C. Vann|first=|title=The Old World's New World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N3wcbe4CEjwC|year=1992|isbn=|location=|pages=|publisher=Oxford University Press}}\n\n===France===\n* Armus, Seth D. ''French Anti-Americanism (1930-1948): Critical Moments in a Complex History'' (2007)  179pp. \n* [[Boyce, Robert]]. \"When \"Uncle Sam\" became 'Uncle Shylock': Sources and Strength of French Anti-Americanism, 1919-1932,\" ''Histoire@Politique'' (April 2013) No. 19 [http://www.histoire-politique.fr/index.php?numero=19&rub=dossier&item=178 text free online scholarly journal; in English]\n* {{cite book|first=Richard Z.|last=Chesnoff|title=The Arrogance of the French: Why They Can't Stand Us \u2013 and Why the Feeling Is Mutual|publisher=Sentinel|date=April 2005|year=|isbn=1-59523-010-6|location=|pages=|url=https://archive.org/details/arroganceoffren00ches}}\n* Kennedy, Sean. \"Andr\u00e9 Siegfried and the Complexities of French Anti-Americanism.\" ''French Politics, Culture & Society'' (2009): 1-22. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/42843597 in JSTOR]\n* Kuisel, Richard F. ''The French Way: How France Embraced and Rejected American Values and Power'' (Princeton University Press, 2013) [https://www.jstor.org/stable/j.ctt7sm7n online]\n* Kuisel, Richard F. ''Seducing the French: the dilemma of Americanization'' (U of California Press, 1993).\n* Lacorne, Denis. \"Anti-Americanism and Americanophobia: A French Perspective\" (2005) [https://hal-sciencespo.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01065572/document online]; also in Denis Lacorne and Tony Judt, eds. ''With Us or Against Us: Studies in Global Anti-Americanism'' (2007) pp 35\u201358\n* Matsumoto, Reiji. \"From Model to Menace: French Intellectuals and American Civilization.\" ''The Japanese Journal of American Studies'' 15 (2004): 163-85. [http://sv121.wadax.ne.jp/~jaas-gr-jp/jjas/PDF/2004/No.15-163.pdf online]\n* Meunier, Sophie. \"Anti-Americanisms in France.\" ''French politics, culture & society'' 23.2 (2005): 126-141.\n* Miller, John J., and Mark Molesky. ''Our oldest enemy: A history of America's disastrous relationship with France'' (Broadway Books, 2007).\n* Ray, Leonard. \"Anti-Americanism and left-right ideology in France.\" ''French Politics'' 9.3 (2011): 201-221.\n* Roger, Philippe.  ''The American Enemy: the history of French anti-Americanism'' (U of Chicago Press, 2005) [https://www.amazon.com/The-American-Enemy-History-Anti-Americanism/dp/0226723690/ excerpt and text search]\n* Rolls, Alistair, and Deborah Walker. ''French and American noir: dark crossings'' (2009).\n* {{cite web|first=Fabrice|last=Serodes|url=http://www.sens-public.org/article.php3?id_article=174|title=L'anglophobie est morte! Vive l'antiam\u00e9ricanisme?|date=|year=2005}}\n* {{cite book|first=David|last=Strauss|title=Menace in the West: The Rise of French Anti-Americanism in Modern Times|publisher=Greenwood Press|year=1978|isbn=0-313-20316-4|location=|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/menaceinwestrise0000stra}}\n* Verhoeven, Tim. \"Shadow and Light: Louis-Xavier Eyma (1816\u201376) and French Opinion of the United States during the Second Empire.\" ''International History Review'' 35.1 (2013): 143-161.\n* Willging, Jennifer. \"Of GMOs, McDomination and foreign fat: contemporary Franco-American food fights.\" ''French Cultural Studies'' 19.2 (2008): 199-226.\n\n===Historiography===\n* Friedman, Max Paul. ''Rethinking Anti-Americanism: The History of an Exceptional Concept in American Foreign Relations'' (Cambridge University Press; 2012) 358 pages. Scholarly history of the concept of anti-Americanism and considers how the idea has affected American politics.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Klautke | first1 = Egbert | year = 2011 | title = Anti-Americanism in Twentieth-Century Europe | url = http://discovery.ucl.ac.uk/1303252/1/Americanization_Revised_May_2011_Historical_Journal.pdf| journal = Historical Journal | volume = 64 | issue = 4| pages = 1125\u20131139 | doi = 10.1017/S0018246X11000276}}\n\n{{Commons category|Anti-Americanism}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{United States topics}}\n{{Cultural criticism}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Anti-Americanism| ]]\n[[Category:American studies]]\n[[Category:Political terminology of the United States]]\n[[Category:Anti-national sentiment]]\n[[Category:Hatred]]\n", "name_user": "MinorEnglishMajor", "label": "safe", "comment": "corrected punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-Americanism"}
{"title_page": "Homing pigeon", "text_new": "{{short description|Pigeons bred to find their way home}}\n{{Redirect|Carrier pigeon|the breed of show pigeon|English Carrier pigeon}}\n[[File:Postduif.jpg|thumb|A messenger  pigeon on a house roof]]\n\nThe true messenger  pigeon is a variety  of [[domestic pigeons]] (''Columba livia domestica'') derived from the wild [[rock dove]], [[selective breeding|selectively bred]] for its ability to find its way home over extremely long distances. The rock dove has an innate homing ability,<ref>{{cite book | last =Blechman | first =Andrew | title =Pigeons-The fascinating saga of the world's most revered and reviled bird | publisher =University of Queensland Press | year =2007 | location =St Lucia, Queensland | url =http://andrewblechman.com/learn_more.html | isbn =978-0-7022-3641-9 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080112210043/http://www.andrewblechman.com/learn_more.html | archivedate =2008-01-12 }}</ref> meaning that it will generally return to its nest (it is believed) using [[magnetoreception]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Levi |first=Wendell |title= The Pigeon | year= 1977 | page=82 | publisher= Levi Publishing Co. |location= Sumter, S.C.|isbn=978-0-85390-013-9 }}</ref> This made it relatively easy to breed from the birds that repeatedly found their way home over long distances. Flights as long as {{convert|1800|km|mi|abbr=in}} have been recorded by birds in competitive [[pigeon racing]].<ref>{{cite journal | last =Walcott | first =Charles | title =Pigeon Homing: Observations,copup and Confusions | journal =Journal of Experimental Biology | url =http://jeb.biologists.org/cgi/reprint/199/1/21.pdf | accessdate =2008-01-04 |pmid=9317262 | year =1996 | volume =199 | issue =Pt 1 | pages =21\u201327}}</ref> Their average flying speed over moderate {{convert|965|km|mi|abbr=in}} distances is around {{convert|60|mph|km/h|abbr=in|order=flip}}<ref name=\"SAW Blechman\">{{cite magazine |last= |author=Andrew |year=2011 |volume=62 |number=2 |title=Cairo's Fancy Fliers |url=http://archive.aramcoworld.com/issue/201102/cairo.s.fancy.fliers.htm |magazine= Saudi Aramco World  |publisher=Aramco Services Company |access-date= 11 December 2018}}</ref> and speeds of up to {{convert|100|mph|km/h|abbr=in|order=flip}} have been observed in top racers for short{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=January 2016}} distances.\n\nBecause of this skill, domesticated pigeons were used to carry messages as '''messenger pigeons'''. They are usually referred to as \"[[pigeon post]]\" if used in post service, or \"[[war pigeon]]\" during wars. Until the introduction of telephones, homing pigeons were used commercially to deliver communication.\n\nMessenger  pigeons are often incorrectly categorized as [[English Carrier pigeon]]s, an ancient breed of [[fancy pigeons]]. They were used historically to send messages but lost the  [[homing instinct]] long ago. Modern-day homing pigeons (homers) or racing pigeons ([[Racing_Homer|racing homers]]) do have \"Carrier blood\" in them because they are in part descendants of the old-style Carriers. This is one reason why they are still commonly but erroneously called \"carrier pigeons\".\n\n==History==\n[[File:Great Barrier Island Pigeon-Gram stamp 1899.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Stamp for early Pigeon-Gram service]]\nBy 3000 BC, Egypt was using  [[homing pigeon]]s for [[pigeon post]], taking advantage of a singular quality of this bird, which when taken far from its nest is able to find its way home due to a particularly developed sense of orientation. Messages were then tied around the legs of the pigeon, which was freed and could reach its original nest. By the 19th century homing pigeons were used extensively for military communications. <ref>Carter W. Clarke, \"Signal Corps Pigeons.\" ''The Military Engineer'' 25.140 (1933): 133-138 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/44563742 Online].</ref>\n\nThe sport of flying messenger pigeons was well-established as early as 3000 years ago.<ref name=PSM36-6>{{cite journal |last=Teale |first=Edwin |title=Mile-a-Minute Pigeons |journal=Popular Science Monthly |date=June 1936 |volume=128 |issue=6 |pages=25ff }}</ref> They were used to proclaim the winner of the [[Ancient Olympic Games|Ancient Olympics]].<ref name=PSM36-6/><ref name=\"Blechman\">{{cite book |last=Blechman |first=Andrew |title=Pigeons \u2014 The fascinating saga of the world's most revered and reviled bird |publisher=University of Queensland Press |year=2007 |location=[[St Lucia, Queensland]] |url=http://www.uqp.uq.edu.au/book_details.php?isbn=9780702236419 |isbn=978-0-7022-3641-9 }}</ref>\nMessenger pigeons were used as early as 1150 in [[Baghdad]]<ref name=fbi>{{cite web |url=http://www.fbipigeons.com/THE%20SPORT.htm |title=The Sport of Racing Homing Pigeons |website=fbipigeons.com }}</ref> and also later by [[Genghis Khan]]. By 1167 a regular service between Baghdad and Syria had been established by Sultan [[Nur ad-Din (died 1174)|Nur ad-Din]].<ref name=\"Allatt 1886\">{{cite journal |last=Allatt |first=Captain H.T.W. |title=The Use of Pigeons as Messengers in War and the Military Pigeon Systems of Europe |journal=[[RUSI Journal]] |year=1886 |volume=30 |pages=107\u2013148 [111] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q8tMAAAAYAAJ |accessdate=24 November 2012 |doi=10.1080/03071848609416366 |issue=133 }}</ref> In [[Damietta]], by the mouth of the Nile, the Spanish traveller [[Pedro Tafur]] saw carrier pigeons for the first time, in 1436, though he imagined that the birds made round trips, out and back.<ref>\"I saw there for the first time carrier pigeons, which take letters in their tail-feathers. They carry them from the place where they are bred to other places, and when the letters are detached they are set free and return to their homes. By this means the inhabitants have speedy news of all who come and go by sea or land.\" (Pedro Tafur, ''[http://depts.washington.edu/silkroad/texts/tafur.html#ch8 Andan\u00e7as e viajes]'').</ref> The [[Republic of Genoa]] equipped their system of watch towers in the Mediterranean Sea with pigeon posts. [[Tipu Sultan]] of [[Kingdom of Mysore|Mysore]] (1750\u20131799) also used messenger pigeons; they returned to the Jamia Masjid mosque in [[Srirangapatna]], which was his headquarters. The pigeon holes may be seen in the mosque's minarets to this day.\n\nIn 1818, a great pigeon race called the ''Cannonball Run'' took place at [[Brussels]].<ref name=PSM36-6/> In 1860, [[Paul Reuter]], who later founded [[Reuters]] press agency, used a fleet of over 45 pigeons to deliver news and stock prices between Brussels and [[Aachen]], the terminus of early telegraph lines. The outcome of the [[Battle of Waterloo]] was also first delivered by a pigeon to England.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thenewsfromwaterloo.com/pigeon-post.html |title=Challenging the myth |accessdate=2017-02-02 }}</ref> During the [[Franco-Prussian War]] pigeons were used to carry mail between besieged Paris and the French unoccupied territory. In December 1870, it took ten hours for a pigeon carrying [[microfilm]]s to fly from [[Perpignan]] to [[Bruxelles]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vieuxpapierspo.blogspot.fr/2014/05/perpignan-bruxelles-par-pigeon-express.html |title=Perpignan\u2013Bruxelles par pigeon-express |last1=Cardenas |first1=Fabricio |date=4 May 2014 |website=Vieux papiers des Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Orientales |language=fr |accessdate=24 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\nHistorically, pigeons carried messages only one way, to their home. They had to be transported manually before another flight. However, by placing their food at one location and their home at another location, pigeons have been trained to fly back and forth up to twice a day reliably, covering round-trip flights up to 160&nbsp;km (100&nbsp;mi).<ref name=\"Micro Live Stock\">{{cite book |last=National Research Council |title= Micro Livestock \u2014 Little Known Small Animals With a Promising Economic Future |year=1991 |publisher=Natl Academy Pr |location=[[Sumter, South Carolina]] |isbn=978-0-309-04437-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7P3DHeYUxhsC }}{{cite web |url=http://diglib.auburn.edu/gsdl/cgi-bin/library?e=d-000-00---0demo--00-0-0--0prompt-10---4------0-1l--1-en-50---20-about---00031-001-1-0utfZz-8-00&cl=CL2.1&d=HASHba5213b5f3493e1ca5e721.5.6&gc=1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-06-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413053800/http://diglib.auburn.edu/gsdl/cgi-bin/library?e=d-000-00---0demo--00-0-0--0prompt-10---4------0-1l--1-en-50---20-about---00031-001-1-0utfZz-8-00&cl=CL2.1&d=HASHba5213b5f3493e1ca5e721.5.6&gc=1 |archivedate=2016-04-13 }}</ref> Their reliability has lent itself to occasional use on mail routes, such as the [[Pigeon post#Pigeon Post of Great Barrier Island (New Zealand)|Great Barrier Pigeongram Service]] established between the [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]], suburb of [[Newton, New Zealand|Newton]] and [[Great Barrier Island]] in November 1897,<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1936/04/12/archives/carrier-pigeons-still-serve-even-in-modern-war-they-do-messenger.html |title=Carrier pigeons still serve; Even in modern war they do messenger duty |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 12, 1936 |page=SM26 }}</ref> possibly the first regular [[air mail]] service in the world. The world's first 'airmail' stamps were issued for the Great Barrier Pigeon-Gram Service from 1898 to 1908.<ref name=\"airmail\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tepapa.govt.nz/wings/pigeons3.htm |title=The Great Barrier Island Pigeon-Gram Service |publisher=[[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415001110/http://www.tepapa.govt.nz/wings/pigeons3.htm |archivedate=2012-04-15 }}</ref>\n\nHoming pigeons were still employed in the 21st century by certain remote police departments in [[Odisha]] state in eastern [[India]] to provide emergency communication services following [[natural disaster]]s. In March 2002, it was announced that India's Police Pigeon Service messenger system in Odisha was to be retired, due to the expanded use of the [[Internet]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/1892085.stm |work=[[BBC News Online]] |title=Indian pigeons lose out to e-mail |date=2002-03-26 |accessdate=2010-03-27 }}</ref> The [[Taliban]] banned the keeping or use of homing pigeons in [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Some of the restrictions imposed by Taliban on women in Afghanistan |publisher=Revolutionary Association of the Women of Afghanistan |url=http://www.rawa.org/rules.htm |accessdate=2008-01-03 }}</ref>\n\nTo this day, pigeons are entered into competitions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pigeonmad.com/beginners_guide_to_racing_pigeons.php |title=Beginners' Guide to Racing Pigeons |website=Pigeon Mad }}</ref>\n\n==Navigation==\n{{main|Animal navigation}}\n\nResearch has been performed with the intention of discovering how pigeons, after being transported, can find their way back from distant places they have never visited before. Most researchers believe that homing ability is based on a \"map and compass\" model, with the compass feature allowing birds to orient and the map feature allowing birds to determine their location relative to a goal site (home loft).<ref name=\"vern\">Bingman, V. P. (1998). Spatial representations and homing pigeon navigation. In S. Healy (Ed). ''Spatial representation in animals''. (pp. 67\u201385). Oxford: Oxford University Press.</ref> While the compass mechanism appears to rely on the sun, the map mechanism has been highly debated.<ref name=\"Walllraff\">{{cite journal | last1 = Wallraff | first1 = H.G. | year = 2004 | title = Avian olfactory navigation: its empirical foundation and conceptual state | url = | journal = Animal Behaviour | volume = 67 | issue = 2| pages = 189\u2013204 | doi=10.1016/j.anbehav.2003.06.007}}</ref> Some researchers believe that the map mechanism relies on the ability of birds to detect the [[Earth's magnetic field]]. \n\nA prominent theory is that the birds are able to detect a magnetic field to help them find their way home. Scientific research previously suggested that on top of a pigeon's beak large number of [[iron]] particles are found which remain aligned to north like a man-made [[compass]], thus it acts as compass which helps pigeon in determining its home. However, a 2012 study disproved{{cn|date=June 2019}} this theory, putting the field back on course to search for an explanation as to how animals detect magnetic fields.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Treiber|first=CD|display-authors=et al|date=2012|title=Clusters of iron-rich cells in the upper beak of pigeons are macrophages not magnetosensitive neurons |url=|journal=Nature|volume=484 |number=7394 |pages=367\u201370|doi=10.1038/nature11046|pmid=22495303|bibcode=2012Natur.484..367T}}</ref> \n\nA light-mediated mechanism that involves the eyes and is lateralized has been examined somewhat, but developments have implicated the trigeminal nerve in [[magnetoception]].<ref name=\"wild\">{{cite journal | last1 = Mora | first1 = C. V. | last2 = Davison | first2 = M. | last3 = Wild | first3 = J. M. | last4 = Walker | first4 = M. M. | year = 2004 | title = Magnetoreception and its trigeminal mediation in the homing pigeon | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 432 | issue = 7016| pages = 508\u2013511 | doi=10.1038/nature03077| pmid = 15565156 | bibcode = 2004Natur.432..508M }}</ref><ref name=\"Gagliardo\">{{cite journal | last1 = Gagliardo | first1 = A. | last2 = Ioale | first2 = P. | last3 = Savini | first3 = M. | last4 = Wild | first4 = J. M. | year = 2006 | title = Having the nerve to home: trigeminal magnetoreceptor versus olfactory mediation of homing in pigeons | url = | journal = The Journal of Experimental Biology | volume = 209 | issue = 15| pages = 2888\u20132892 | doi=10.1242/jeb.02313| pmid = 16857872 }}</ref> Research by Floriano Papi (Italy, early 1970s) and more recent work, largely by Hans Wallraff, suggest that pigeons also orient themselves using the spatial distribution of atmospheric odors,<ref name=\"Walllraff\" /> known as [[olfactory navigation]].\n\nOther research indicates that homing pigeons also navigate through visual landmarks by following familiar roads and other man-made features, making 90-degree turns and following habitual routes, much the same way that humans navigate.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/3460977.stm|title=Pigeons reveal map reading secret|date=2004-02-05|accessdate=2008-07-02|publisher=BBC News (5 Feb, 2004)}}</ref>\n\nResearch by Jon Hagstrum of the US Geological Survey suggests that homing pigeons use low-frequency [[infrasound]] to navigate.<ref name=\"Knight\">Knight, Kathryn (2013). Disappearing homing pigeon mystery solved. The Company of Biologists. Retrieved 2013-01-31</ref> Sound waves as low 0.1&nbsp;Hz have been observed to disrupt or redirect pigeon navigation. The pigeon ear, being far too small to interpret such a long wave, directs pigeons to fly in a circle when first taking air, in order to mentally map such long infrasound waves.\n\nVarious experiments suggest that different breeds of homing pigeons rely on different cues to different extents. Charles Walcott at Cornell University was able to demonstrate that while pigeons from one loft were confused by a magnetic anomaly in the Earth it had no effect on birds from another loft {{convert|1|mi|km|abbr=in|order=flip}} away. Other experiments have shown that altering the perceived time of day with artificial lighting or using air conditioning to eliminate odors in the pigeons' home roost affected the pigeons' ability to return home.{{Citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nGPS tracing studies indicate that gravitational anomalies may play a role as well.\n<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Nicole Blaser|author2=Sergei I. Guskov|author3=Virginia Meskenaite|author4=Valerii A. Kanevskyi|author5=Hans-Peter Lipp|title=Altered Orientation and Flight Paths of Pigeons Reared on Gravity Anomalies: A GPS Tracking Study|journal=PLoS ONE |date=October 23, 2013|volume=8|issue=10|pages=e77102|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0077102|pmid=24194860|bibcode=2013PLoSO...877102B|pmc=3806762}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Nicole Blaser|author2=Sergei I. Guskov|author3=Vladimir A. Entin|author4=David P. Wolfer|author5=Valeryi A. Kanevskyi|author6=Hans-Peter Lipp|title=Gravity anomalies without geomagnetic disturbances interfere with pigeon homing \u2013 a GPS tracking study|journal=Journal of Experimental Biology|volume=217|issue=22|date=2014|pages=4057\u20134067|doi=10.1242/jeb.108670|pmid=25392461}}</ref>\n\n==Roles==\n\n===Postal carriage===\n{{Main|Pigeon post}}\n\nWhen used as carrier pigeons in [[pigeon post]] a message is written on thin light paper and rolled into a small tube attached to the bird's leg. Pigeons can only go back to one \"mentally marked\" point that they have identified as their home, so \"pigeon mail\" can only work when the sender is actually holding the receiver's pigeons. White homing pigeons are used in [[release dove|dove-releasing]] ceremonies at weddings, funerals, and some sporting events.\n\nWith training, pigeons can carry up to 75&nbsp;g (2.5&nbsp;oz) on their backs. The German apothecary [[Julius Neubronner]] used carrier pigeons to deliver urgent medication.<ref>{{Cite journal|ref=CITEREFLes Nouveaut\u00e9s Photographiques1910|title=Le pigeon voyageur photographe|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k54904907.image.r=Neubronner.f70.vignettesnaviguer.langEN|year=1910|journal=Les Nouveaut\u00e9s Photographiques|pages=63\u201371|language=French}}</ref> In 1977 a similar carrier pigeon service was set up for the transport of laboratory specimens between two English hospitals. Every morning a basket with pigeons was taken from Plymouth General Hospital to Devonport Hospital. The birds then delivered unbreakable vials back to Plymouth as needed.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19770723&id=Y9MVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5xEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3259,4076496 Pigeons flying for life], ''The Milwaukee Sentinel'' \u2013 July 23, 1977</ref> The 30 carrier pigeons became unnecessary in 1983 because of the closure of one of the hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1106&context=icwdmprobe |title=The Probe: Newsletter of the National Animal Damage Control Association, Issue 33 \u2013 June 1983 |date= |accessdate=2013-08-14}}</ref> In the 1980s a similar system existed between two French hospitals located in Granville and Avranche.<ref>{{url|https://web.archive.org/web/20120311215220/http://www.abc.terre.defense.gouv.fr/sites/abc.terre.defense.gouv.fr/IMG/pdf/carabinier_15.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Wartime communication===\n{{main|War pigeon}}\n[[File:Bus pigeon loft.jpg|thumb|150px|right|A B-type bus from London converted into a pigeon loft for use in northern France and Belgium during the First World War]]\n[[File:Abfertigen einer Meldung durch Brieftauben - CH-BAR - 3240471 - restoration.jpg| Dispatching of a message by carrier pigeon within the Swiss Army during World War I|thumb|150px]]\nBirds were used extensively during [[World War I]]. One homing pigeon, [[Cher Ami]], was awarded the French [[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de guerre]] for her heroic service in delivering 12 important messages, despite having been very badly injured.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Webley|first1=Kayla|title=Top 10 Heroic Animals|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2059858_2059863_2060209,00.html|accessdate=17 January 2017|agency=Time Magazine|date=21 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Avro Lancaster pigeons WWII IWM TR 193.jpg|thumb|left|Crewman with homing pigeons carried in bombers as a means of communications in the event of a crash, ditching, or radio failure]]\n\nDuring World War II, the Irish [[Paddy (pigeon)|Paddy]], the American [[G.I. Joe (pigeon)|G.I. Joe]] and the English [[Mary of Exeter]] all received the [[Dickin Medal]]. They were among 32 pigeons to receive this award, for their gallantry and bravery in saving human lives with their actions. Eighty-two homing pigeons were dropped into the [[Netherlands]] with the First Airborne Division Signals as part of [[Operation Market Garden]] in [[World War II]]. The pigeons' loft was located in London, which would have required them to fly {{convert|240|mi|km|abbr=in|order=flip}} to deliver their messages.<ref name=bridge>[[Cornelius Ryan]] - ''[[A Bridge Too Far (book)|A Bridge Too Far]]''</ref> Also in World War II, hundreds of homing pigeons with the [[Source Columba|Confidential Pigeon Service]] were airdropped into northwest Europe to serve as intelligence vectors for local resistance agents. Birds played a vital part in the [[Normandy Landings|Invasion of Normandy]] as radios could not be used for fear of vital information being intercepted by the enemy.\n\n===Computing===\nThe humorous [[IP over Avian Carriers]] (RFC 1149) is an [[Internet]] protocol for the transmission of messages via homing pigeon. Originally intended as an [[April Fools' Day RFC]] entry, this protocol was implemented and used, once, to transmit a message in [[Bergen]], [[Norway]], on April 28, 2001.<ref name=bergen>{{cite web|url=http://www.blug.linux.no/rfc1149/|title=RFC-1149|website=BLUG|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004221306/http://www.blug.linux.no/rfc1149/|archivedate=2011-10-04}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2009, a [[South Africa]]n IT company based in [[Durban]] pitted an 11-month-old bird armed with a data packed 4&nbsp;GB memory stick against the [[ADSL]] service from the country's biggest Internet service provider, [[Telkom SA|Telkom]]. The pigeon, Winston, took an hour and eight minutes to carry the data {{convert|80|km|mi|abbr=in}}. In all, the data transfer took two hours, six minutes, and fifty-seven seconds\u2014the same amount of time it took to transfer 4% of the data over the ADSL.<ref>{{cite news | title =Pigeon transfers data faster than South Africa's Telkom| publisher =Reuters (September 9, 2009)| url =https://www.reuters.com/article/oddlyEnoughNews/idUSTRE5885PM20090909 | accessdate =2009-10-09 | first=Peroshni | last=Govender | date=2009-09-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title =SA pigeon 'faster than broadband'| publisher =BBC (September 10, 2009)| url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/8248056.stm | accessdate =2009-10-09 | date=2009-09-10}}</ref>\n\n===Smuggling===\nHoming pigeons have been reported to be used as a smuggling technique, getting objects and narcotics across borders and into prisons.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/cocaine-smuggling-carrier-pigeons|title=Cocaine carrier pigeons are the latest drug smuggling technique|last=Quilty-Harper|first=Conrad|work=British GQ|access-date=2017-05-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> For instance, between 2009 and 2015, pigeons have been reported to carry [[cell phones]], [[SIM cards]], phone [[Battery (electricity)|batteries]] and [[USB]] cords into prisons in the [[Brazil]]ian state of [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]].<ref>{{cite web|author=G1 S\u00e3o Paulo |url=http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/SaoPaulo/0,,MUL1101091-5605,00-POMBO+QUE+LEVAVA+CELULAR+PARA+PRESOS+E+CAPTURADO+NO+INTERIOR+DE+SP.html |title=Pombo que levava celular para presos \u00e9 capturado no interior de SP (Portuguese) |date=April 28, 2009 |publisher=G1 |accessdate=October 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=G1 S\u00e3o Paulo |url=http://g1.globo.com/sao-paulo/noticia/2015/08/pombo-com-celular-e-encontrado-em-penitenciaria-na-zona-sul-de-sp.html |title=Pombo com celular \u00e9 encontrado em penitenci\u00e1ria na Zona Sul de SP (Portuguese) |date=August 4, 2015 |publisher=G1 |accessdate=October 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Animal Exploitation==\nPigeon races are sometimes considered as a type of animal exploitation and against animal welfare, particularly where betting is involved, and animal welfare is regarded as secondary. For example, the animal welfare organisation [[PETA]] criticises Taiwanese owners for flying birds across wide oceans where few reach their destination, claiming a fatality rate of 98%. <ref>[Https://example.org https://support.peta.org/page/4206/action/1] Investigation on Pigeon Races</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of pigeon breeds]]\n* [[American Show Racer]]\n* [[Dovecote]]\n* [[Homing Chicken]]\n* [[Pigeon intelligence]]\n* [[Pigeon photography]]\n* [[Tippler]]\n* [[Otto J. Zahn]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Lucy M Blanchard, ''Chico, the Story of a Homing Pigeon in the Great War'', Diggory Press, {{ISBN|978-1-84685-039-4}}\n* Carter W. Clarke,  \"Signal Corps Pigeons.\" ''The Military Engineer'' 25.140 (1933): 133-138 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/44563742 Online].\n* [[Jon Day (writer)|Jon Day]], \"Operation Columba\" (review of [[Gordon Corera]], ''Secret Pigeon Service'', William Collins, 2018, 326 pp., {{ISBN|978 0 00 822030 3}}), ''[[London Review of Books]]'', vol. 41, no. 7 (4 April 2019), pp.&nbsp;15\u201316.  \"Pigeons flew across theRoman Empire carrying messages from the margins to the capital.  [In 43 BCE] [[Decimus Junius Brutus Albinus|Decimus Brutus]] broke [[Marc Antony]]'s [[Battle of Mutina|siege of Mutina]] [Modena, in northern Italy] by sending letters to the consuls via pigeon.... [However, p]igeons only really came into their own with modern [times, especially d]uring the 19th and early 20th centuries...\"  ([[Jon Day (writer)|Jon Day]], p.&nbsp;15.) \n* [[Meir Shalev]], ''A Pigeon and a Boy'' (English translation by Evan Fallenberg), a historical novel about the use of pigeons by the [[Israel Defense Force]]s (and the Haganah before Israel was founded in 1948) in the defence of Israel when it was first founded, and in the defence of the Jewish community before Israeli independence\n* [[Jerry Spinelli]], ''Wringer'' \n* {{cite book|last=Tegetmeier|first=William Bernhard|title=The homing or carrier pigeon|year=1871|publisher=George Routledge|location=London}}\n* [http://www.hackemerlofts.com/articles.html \"Nine Champions Create A Champion\"], Bob Kinney Silverado, ''The Thoroughbred'', 15 May 1998\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Homing pigeons}}\n* [http://pigeoncomm.site90.net/ Pigeon and Business and Communication]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051217093543/http://www.txtwriter.com/Onscience/Articles/pigeons.html The great pigeon race disaster of 97 suggests an answer to an enduring mystery], George Johnson, \"ON SCIENCE\", ''[[St. Louis Post Dispatch]]''\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/dirs/1/4/9/9/14990/14990-h/14990-h.htm#art10 The System of Military Dovecotes in Europe] from an 1891 ''[[Scientific American]]'' article at [[Project Gutenberg]]\n* Joao Moreira Tavares: [https://encyclopedia.1914-1918-online.net/article/carrier_pigeons_portugal/ Carrier Pigeons (Portugal)], in: [https://encyclopedia.1914-1918-online.net/home.html/ 1914-1918-online. International Encyclopedia of the First World War].\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090601232918/http://silvio-co.com/pigeons/ Resource for pigeon racers]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=nCcDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA49 Round Trip War Birds], ''[[Popular Science]]'', November 1941, article on [[US Army Signal Corps]] use of homing pigeons with first high-speed photos showing how a pigeon flies\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Uh8QlfQ26Q Fragment 'Those waiting for the birds'] (2008, Eve Duchemin), documentary about Belgian homing pigeons\n* {{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p-IDAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA195&dq=Popular%20Science%201930%20plane%20%22Popular%20Mechanics%22&pg=PA194#v=onepage&q&f=true |title=The Passing of the Carrier Pigeon|journal=Popular Mechanics |date=February 1930|pages= 194\u2013197|last1=Miller|first1=James Nevin}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airmail]]\n[[Category:Animal-powered transport]]\n[[Category:Animals in sport]]\n[[Category:Domestic pigeons]]\n[[Category:Pigeon breeds]]\n[[Category:History of telecommunications]]\n[[Category:Pigeon racing]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pigeons bred to find their way home}}\n{{Redirect|Carrier pigeon|the breed of show pigeon|English Carrier pigeon}}\n[[File:Postduif.jpg|thumb|A messenger  pigeon on a house roof]]\n\nThe true messenger  pigeon is a variety  of [[domestic pigeons]] (''Columba livia domestica'') derived from the wild [[rock dove]], [[selective breeding|selectively bred]] for its ability to find its way home over extremely long distances. The rock dove has an innate homing ability,<ref>{{cite book | last =Blechman | first =Andrew | title =Pigeons-The fascinating saga of the world's most revered and reviled bird | publisher =University of Queensland Press | year =2007 | location =St Lucia, Queensland | url =http://andrewblechman.com/learn_more.html | isbn =978-0-7022-3641-9 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080112210043/http://www.andrewblechman.com/learn_more.html | archivedate =2008-01-12 }}</ref> meaning that it will generally return to its nest (it is believed) using [[magnetoreception]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Levi |first=Wendell |title= The Pigeon | year= 1977 | page=82 | publisher= Levi Publishing Co. |location= Sumter, S.C.|isbn=978-0-85390-013-9 }}</ref> This made it relatively easy to breed from the birds that repeatedly found their way home over long distances. Flights as long as {{convert|1800|km|mi|abbr=in}} have been recorded by birds in competitive [[pigeon racing]].<ref>{{cite journal | last =Walcott | first =Charles | title =Pigeon Homing: Observations,copup and Confusions | journal =Journal of Experimental Biology | url =http://jeb.biologists.org/cgi/reprint/199/1/21.pdf | accessdate =2008-01-04 |pmid=9317262 | year =1996 | volume =199 | issue =Pt 1 | pages =21\u201327}}</ref> Their average flying speed over moderate {{convert|965|km|mi|abbr=in}} distances is around {{convert|60|mph|km/h|abbr=in|order=flip}}<ref name=\"SAW Blechman\">{{cite magazine |last= |author=Andrew |year=2011 |volume=62 |number=2 |title=Cairo's Fancy Fliers |url=http://archive.aramcoworld.com/issue/201102/cairo.s.fancy.fliers.htm |magazine= Saudi Aramco World  |publisher=Aramco Services Company |access-date= 11 December 2018}}</ref> and speeds of up to {{convert|100|mph|km/h|abbr=in|order=flip}} have been observed in top racers for short{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=January 2016}} distances.\n\nBecause of this skill, domesticated pigeons were used to carry messages as '''messenger pigeons'''. They are usually referred to as \"[[pigeon post]]\" if used in post service, or \"[[war pigeon]]\" during wars. Until the introduction of telephones, homing pigeons were used commercially to deliver communication.\n\nMessenger  pigeons are often incorrectly categorized as [[English Carrier pigeon]]s, an ancient breed of [[fancy pigeons]]. They were used historically to send messages but lost the  [[homing instinct]] long ago. Modern-day homing pigeons (homers) or racing pigeons ([[Racing_Homer|racing homers]]) do have \"Carrier blood\" in them because they are in part descendants of the old-style Carriers. This is one reason why they are still commonly but erroneously called \"carrier pigeons\".\n\n==History==\n[[File:Great Barrier Island Pigeon-Gram stamp 1899.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Stamp for early Pigeon-Gram service]]\nBy 3000 BC, Egypt was using  [[homing pigeon]]s for [[pigeon post]], taking advantage of a singular quality of this bird, which when taken far from its nest is able to find its way home due to a particularly developed sense of orientation. Messages were then tied around the legs of the pigeon, which was freed and could reach its original nest. By the 19th century homing pigeons were used extensively for military communications. <ref>Carter W. Clarke, \"Signal Corps Pigeons.\" ''The Military Engineer'' 25.140 (1933): 133-138 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/44563742 Online].</ref>\n\nThe sport of flying messenger pigeons was well-established as early as 3000 years ago.<ref name=PSM36-6>{{cite journal |last=Teale |first=Edwin |title=Mile-a-Minute Pigeons |journal=Popular Science Monthly |date=June 1936 |volume=128 |issue=6 |pages=25ff }}</ref> They were used to proclaim the winner of the [[Ancient Olympic Games|Ancient Olympics]].<ref name=PSM36-6/><ref name=\"Blechman\">{{cite book |last=Blechman |first=Andrew |title=Pigeons \u2014 The fascinating saga of the world's most revered and reviled bird |publisher=University of Queensland Press |year=2007 |location=[[St Lucia, Queensland]] |url=http://www.uqp.uq.edu.au/book_details.php?isbn=9780702236419 |isbn=978-0-7022-3641-9 }}</ref>\nMessenger pigeons were used as early as 1150 in [[Baghdad]]<ref name=fbi>{{cite web |url=http://www.fbipigeons.com/THE%20SPORT.htm |title=The Sport of Racing Homing Pigeons |website=fbipigeons.com }}</ref> and also later by [[Genghis Khan]]. By 1167 a regular service between Baghdad and Syria had been established by Sultan [[Nur ad-Din (died 1174)|Nur ad-Din]].<ref name=\"Allatt 1886\">{{cite journal |last=Allatt |first=Captain H.T.W. |title=The Use of Pigeons as Messengers in War and the Military Pigeon Systems of Europe |journal=[[RUSI Journal]] |year=1886 |volume=30 |pages=107\u2013148 [111] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q8tMAAAAYAAJ |accessdate=24 November 2012 |doi=10.1080/03071848609416366 |issue=133 }}</ref> In [[Damietta]], by the mouth of the Nile, the Spanish traveller [[Pedro Tafur]] saw carrier pigeons for the first time, in 1436, though he imagined that the birds made round trips, out and back.<ref>\"I saw there for the first time carrier pigeons, which take letters in their tail-feathers. They carry them from the place where they are bred to other places, and when the letters are detached they are set free and return to their homes. By this means the inhabitants have speedy news of all who come and go by sea or land.\" (Pedro Tafur, ''[http://depts.washington.edu/silkroad/texts/tafur.html#ch8 Andan\u00e7as e viajes]'').</ref> The [[Republic of Genoa]] equipped their system of watch towers in the Mediterranean Sea with pigeon posts. [[Tipu Sultan]] of [[Kingdom of Mysore|Mysore]] (1750\u20131799) also used messenger pigeons; they returned to the Jamia Masjid mosque in [[Srirangapatna]], which was his headquarters. The pigeon holes may be seen in the mosque's minarets to this day.\n\nIn 1818, a great pigeon race called the ''Cannonball Run'' took place at [[Brussels]].<ref name=PSM36-6/> In 1860, [[Paul Reuter]], who later founded [[Reuters]] press agency, used a fleet of over 45 pigeons to deliver news and stock prices between Brussels and [[Aachen]], the terminus of early telegraph lines. The outcome of the [[Battle of Waterloo]] was also first delivered by a pigeon to England.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thenewsfromwaterloo.com/pigeon-post.html |title=Challenging the myth |accessdate=2017-02-02 }}</ref> During the [[Franco-Prussian War]] pigeons were used to carry mail between besieged Paris and the French unoccupied territory. In December 1870, it took ten hours for a pigeon carrying [[microfilm]]s to fly from [[Perpignan]] to [[Bruxelles]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://vieuxpapierspo.blogspot.fr/2014/05/perpignan-bruxelles-par-pigeon-express.html |title=Perpignan\u2013Bruxelles par pigeon-express |last1=Cardenas |first1=Fabricio |date=4 May 2014 |website=Vieux papiers des Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Orientales |language=fr |accessdate=24 February 2016 }}</ref>\n\nHistorically, pigeons carried messages only one way, to their home. They had to be transported manually before another flight. However, by placing their food at one location and their home at another location, pigeons have been trained to fly back and forth up to twice a day reliably, covering round-trip flights up to 160&nbsp;km (100&nbsp;mi).<ref name=\"Micro Live Stock\">{{cite book |last=National Research Council |title= Micro Livestock \u2014 Little Known Small Animals With a Promising Economic Future |year=1991 |publisher=Natl Academy Pr |location=[[Sumter, South Carolina]] |isbn=978-0-309-04437-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7P3DHeYUxhsC }}{{cite web |url=http://diglib.auburn.edu/gsdl/cgi-bin/library?e=d-000-00---0demo--00-0-0--0prompt-10---4------0-1l--1-en-50---20-about---00031-001-1-0utfZz-8-00&cl=CL2.1&d=HASHba5213b5f3493e1ca5e721.5.6&gc=1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-06-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413053800/http://diglib.auburn.edu/gsdl/cgi-bin/library?e=d-000-00---0demo--00-0-0--0prompt-10---4------0-1l--1-en-50---20-about---00031-001-1-0utfZz-8-00&cl=CL2.1&d=HASHba5213b5f3493e1ca5e721.5.6&gc=1 |archivedate=2016-04-13 }}</ref> Their reliability has lent itself to occasional use on mail routes, such as the [[Pigeon post#Pigeon Post of Great Barrier Island (New Zealand)|Great Barrier Pigeongram Service]] established between the [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]], suburb of [[Newton, New Zealand|Newton]] and [[Great Barrier Island]] in November 1897,<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1936/04/12/archives/carrier-pigeons-still-serve-even-in-modern-war-they-do-messenger.html |title=Carrier pigeons still serve; Even in modern war they do messenger duty |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 12, 1936 |page=SM26 }}</ref> possibly the first regular [[air mail]] service in the world. The world's first 'airmail' stamps were issued for the Great Barrier Pigeon-Gram Service from 1898 to 1908.<ref name=\"airmail\">{{cite web |url=http://www.tepapa.govt.nz/wings/pigeons3.htm |title=The Great Barrier Island Pigeon-Gram Service |publisher=[[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415001110/http://www.tepapa.govt.nz/wings/pigeons3.htm |archivedate=2012-04-15 }}</ref>\n\nHoming pigeons were still employed in the 21st century by certain remote police departments in [[Odisha]] state in eastern [[India]] to provide emergency communication services following [[natural disaster]]s. In March 2002, it was announced that India's Police Pigeon Service messenger system in Odisha was to be retired, due to the expanded use of the [[Internet]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/1892085.stm |work=[[BBC News Online]] |title=Indian pigeons lose out to e-mail |date=2002-03-26 |accessdate=2010-03-27 }}</ref> The [[Taliban]] banned the keeping or use of homing pigeons in [[Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Some of the restrictions imposed by Taliban on women in Afghanistan |publisher=Revolutionary Association of the Women of Afghanistan |url=http://www.rawa.org/rules.htm |accessdate=2008-01-03 }}</ref>\n\nTo this day, pigeons are entered into competitions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pigeonmad.com/beginners_guide_to_racing_pigeons.php |title=Beginners' Guide to Racing Pigeons |website=Pigeon Mad }}</ref>\n\n==Navigation==\n{{main|Animal navigation}}\n\nResearch has been performed with the intention of discovering how pigeons, after being transported, can find their way back from distant places they have never visited before. Most researchers believe that homing ability is based on a \"map and compass\" model, with the compass feature allowing birds to orient and the map feature allowing birds to determine their location relative to a goal site (home loft).<ref name=\"vern\">Bingman, V. P. (1998). Spatial representations and homing pigeon navigation. In S. Healy (Ed). ''Spatial representation in animals''. (pp. 67\u201385). Oxford: Oxford University Press.</ref> While the compass mechanism appears to rely on the sun, the map mechanism has been highly debated.<ref name=\"Walllraff\">{{cite journal | last1 = Wallraff | first1 = H.G. | year = 2004 | title = Avian olfactory navigation: its empirical foundation and conceptual state | url = | journal = Animal Behaviour | volume = 67 | issue = 2| pages = 189\u2013204 | doi=10.1016/j.anbehav.2003.06.007}}</ref> Some researchers believe that the map mechanism relies on the ability of birds to detect the [[Earth's magnetic field]]. \n\nA prominent theory is that the birds are able to detect a magnetic field to help them find their way home. Scientific research previously suggested that on top of a pigeon's beak large number of [[iron]] particles are found which remain aligned to north like a man-made [[compass]], thus it acts as compass which helps pigeon in determining its home. However, a 2012 study disproved{{cn|date=June 2019}} this theory, putting the field back on course to search for an explanation as to how animals detect magnetic fields.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Treiber|first=CD|display-authors=et al|date=2012|title=Clusters of iron-rich cells in the upper beak of pigeons are macrophages not magnetosensitive neurons |url=|journal=Nature|volume=484 |number=7394 |pages=367\u201370|doi=10.1038/nature11046|pmid=22495303|bibcode=2012Natur.484..367T}}</ref> \n\nA light-mediated mechanism that involves the eyes and is lateralized has been examined somewhat, but developments have implicated the trigeminal nerve in [[magnetoception]].<ref name=\"wild\">{{cite journal | last1 = Mora | first1 = C. V. | last2 = Davison | first2 = M. | last3 = Wild | first3 = J. M. | last4 = Walker | first4 = M. M. | year = 2004 | title = Magnetoreception and its trigeminal mediation in the homing pigeon | url = | journal = Nature | volume = 432 | issue = 7016| pages = 508\u2013511 | doi=10.1038/nature03077| pmid = 15565156 | bibcode = 2004Natur.432..508M }}</ref><ref name=\"Gagliardo\">{{cite journal | last1 = Gagliardo | first1 = A. | last2 = Ioale | first2 = P. | last3 = Savini | first3 = M. | last4 = Wild | first4 = J. M. | year = 2006 | title = Having the nerve to home: trigeminal magnetoreceptor versus olfactory mediation of homing in pigeons | url = | journal = The Journal of Experimental Biology | volume = 209 | issue = 15| pages = 2888\u20132892 | doi=10.1242/jeb.02313| pmid = 16857872 }}</ref> Research by Floriano Papi (Italy, early 1970s) and more recent work, largely by Hans Wallraff, suggest that pigeons also orient themselves using the spatial distribution of atmospheric odors,<ref name=\"Walllraff\" /> known as [[olfactory navigation]].\n\nOther research indicates that homing pigeons also navigate through visual landmarks by following familiar roads and other man-made features, making 90-degree turns and following habitual routes, much the same way that humans navigate.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/3460977.stm|title=Pigeons reveal map reading secret|date=2004-02-05|accessdate=2008-07-02|publisher=BBC News (5 Feb, 2004)}}</ref>\n\nResearch by Jon Hagstrum of the US Geological Survey suggests that homing pigeons use low-frequency [[infrasound]] to navigate.<ref name=\"Knight\">Knight, Kathryn (2013). Disappearing homing pigeon mystery solved. The Company of Biologists. Retrieved 2013-01-31</ref> Sound waves as low 0.1&nbsp;Hz have been observed to disrupt or redirect pigeon navigation. The pigeon ear, being far too small to interpret such a long wave, directs pigeons to fly in a circle when first taking air, in order to mentally map such long infrasound waves.\n\nVarious experiments suggest that different breeds of homing pigeons rely on different cues to different extents. Charles Walcott at Cornell University was able to demonstrate that while pigeons from one loft were confused by a magnetic anomaly in the Earth it had no effect on birds from another loft {{convert|1|mi|km|abbr=in|order=flip}} away. Other experiments have shown that altering the perceived time of day with artificial lighting or using air conditioning to eliminate odors in the pigeons' home roost affected the pigeons' ability to return home.{{Citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nGPS tracing studies indicate that gravitational anomalies may play a role as well.\n<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Nicole Blaser|author2=Sergei I. Guskov|author3=Virginia Meskenaite|author4=Valerii A. Kanevskyi|author5=Hans-Peter Lipp|title=Altered Orientation and Flight Paths of Pigeons Reared on Gravity Anomalies: A GPS Tracking Study|journal=PLoS ONE |date=October 23, 2013|volume=8|issue=10|pages=e77102|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0077102|pmid=24194860|bibcode=2013PLoSO...877102B|pmc=3806762}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Nicole Blaser|author2=Sergei I. Guskov|author3=Vladimir A. Entin|author4=David P. Wolfer|author5=Valeryi A. Kanevskyi|author6=Hans-Peter Lipp|title=Gravity anomalies without geomagnetic disturbances interfere with pigeon homing \u2013 a GPS tracking study|journal=Journal of Experimental Biology|volume=217|issue=22|date=2014|pages=4057\u20134067|doi=10.1242/jeb.108670|pmid=25392461}}</ref>\n\n==Roles==\n\n===Postal carriage===\n{{Main|Pigeon post}}\n\nWhen used as carrier pigeons in [[pigeon post]] a message is written on thin light paper and rolled into a small tube attached to the bird's leg. Pigeons can only go back to one \"mentally marked\" point that they have identified as their home, so \"pigeon mail\" can only work when the sender is actually holding the receiver's pigeons. White homing pigeons are used in [[release dove|dove-releasing]] ceremonies at weddings, funerals, and some sporting events.\n\nWith training, pigeons can carry up to 75&nbsp;g (2.5&nbsp;oz) on their backs. The German apothecary [[Julius Neubronner]] used carrier pigeons to deliver urgent medication.<ref>{{Cite journal|ref=CITEREFLes Nouveaut\u00e9s Photographiques1910|title=Le pigeon voyageur photographe|url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k54904907.image.r=Neubronner.f70.vignettesnaviguer.langEN|year=1910|journal=Les Nouveaut\u00e9s Photographiques|pages=63\u201371|language=French}}</ref> In 1977 a similar carrier pigeon service was set up for the transport of laboratory specimens between two English hospitals. Every morning a basket with pigeons was taken from Plymouth General Hospital to Devonport Hospital. The birds then delivered unbreakable vials back to Plymouth as needed.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19770723&id=Y9MVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5xEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3259,4076496 Pigeons flying for life], ''The Milwaukee Sentinel'' \u2013 July 23, 1977</ref> The 30 carrier pigeons became unnecessary in 1983 because of the closure of one of the hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1106&context=icwdmprobe |title=The Probe: Newsletter of the National Animal Damage Control Association, Issue 33 \u2013 June 1983 |date= |accessdate=2013-08-14}}</ref> In the 1980s a similar system existed between two French hospitals located in Granville and Avranche.<ref>{{url|https://web.archive.org/web/20120311215220/http://www.abc.terre.defense.gouv.fr/sites/abc.terre.defense.gouv.fr/IMG/pdf/carabinier_15.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Wartime communication===\n{{main|War pigeon}}\n[[File:Bus pigeon loft.jpg|thumb|150px|right|A B-type bus from London converted into a pigeon loft for use in northern France and Belgium during the First World War]]\n[[File:Abfertigen einer Meldung durch Brieftauben - CH-BAR - 3240471 - restoration.jpg| Dispatching of a message by carrier pigeon within the Swiss Army during World War I|thumb|150px]]\nBirds were used extensively during [[World War I]]. One homing pigeon, [[Cher Ami]], was awarded the French [[Croix de guerre 1914\u20131918 (France)|Croix de guerre]] for her heroic service in delivering 12 important messages, despite having been very badly injured.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Webley|first1=Kayla|title=Top 10 Heroic Animals|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2059858_2059863_2060209,00.html|accessdate=17 January 2017|agency=Time Magazine|date=21 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Avro Lancaster pigeons WWII IWM TR 193.jpg|thumb|left|Crewman with homing pigeons carried in bombers as a means of communications in the event of a crash, ditching, or radio failure]]\n\nDuring World War II, the Irish [[Paddy (pigeon)|Paddy]], the American [[G.I. Joe (pigeon)|G.I. Joe]] and the English [[Mary of Exeter]] all received the [[Dickin Medal]]. They were among 32 pigeons to receive this award, for their gallantry and bravery in saving human lives with their actions. Eighty-two homing pigeons were dropped into the [[Netherlands]] with the First Airborne Division Signals as part of [[Operation Market Garden]] in [[World War II]]. The pigeons' loft was located in London, which would have required them to fly {{convert|240|mi|km|abbr=in|order=flip}} to deliver their messages.<ref name=bridge>[[Cornelius Ryan]] - ''[[A Bridge Too Far (book)|A Bridge Too Far]]''</ref> Also in World War II, hundreds of homing pigeons with the [[Source Columba|Confidential Pigeon Service]] were airdropped into northwest Europe to serve as intelligence vectors for local resistance agents. Birds played a vital part in the [[Normandy Landings|Invasion of Normandy]] as radios could not be used for fear of vital information being intercepted by the enemy.\n\n===Computing===\nThe humorous [[IP over Avian Carriers]] (RFC 1149) is an [[Internet]] protocol for the transmission of messages via homing pigeon. Originally intended as an [[April Fools' Day RFC]] entry, this protocol was implemented and used, once, to transmit a message in [[Bergen]], [[Norway]], on April 28, 2001.<ref name=bergen>{{cite web|url=http://www.blug.linux.no/rfc1149/|title=RFC-1149|website=BLUG|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004221306/http://www.blug.linux.no/rfc1149/|archivedate=2011-10-04}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2009, a [[South Africa]]n IT company based in [[Durban]] pitted an 11-month-old bird armed with a data packed 4&nbsp;GB memory stick against the [[ADSL]] service from the country's biggest Internet service provider, [[Telkom SA|Telkom]]. The pigeon, Winston, took an hour and eight minutes to carry the data {{convert|80|km|mi|abbr=in}}. In all, the data transfer took two hours, six minutes, and fifty-seven seconds\u2014the same amount of time it took to transfer 4% of the data \n<references />\nover the ADSL.<ref>{{cite news | title =Pigeon transfers data faster than South Africa's Telkom| publisher =Reuters (September 9, 2009)| url =https://www.reuters.com/article/oddlyEnoughNews/idUSTRE5885PM20090909 | accessdate =2009-10-09 | first=Peroshni | last=Govender | date=2009-09-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title =SA pigeon 'faster than broadband'| publisher =BBC (September 10, 2009)| url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/8248056.stm | accessdate =2009-10-09 | date=2009-09-10}}</ref>\n\n===Smuggling===\nHoming pigeons have been reported to be used as a smuggling technique, getting objects and narcotics across borders and into prisons.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gq-magazine.co.uk/article/cocaine-smuggling-carrier-pigeons|title=Cocaine carrier pigeons are the latest drug smuggling technique|last=Quilty-Harper|first=Conrad|work=British GQ|access-date=2017-05-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> For instance, between 2009 and 2015, pigeons have been reported to carry [[cell phones]], [[SIM cards]], phone [[Battery (electricity)|batteries]] and [[USB]] cords into prisons in the [[Brazil]]ian state of [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]].<ref>{{cite web|author=G1 S\u00e3o Paulo |url=http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/SaoPaulo/0,,MUL1101091-5605,00-POMBO+QUE+LEVAVA+CELULAR+PARA+PRESOS+E+CAPTURADO+NO+INTERIOR+DE+SP.html |title=Pombo que levava celular para presos \u00e9 capturado no interior de SP (Portuguese) |date=April 28, 2009 |publisher=G1 |accessdate=October 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=G1 S\u00e3o Paulo |url=http://g1.globo.com/sao-paulo/noticia/2015/08/pombo-com-celular-e-encontrado-em-penitenciaria-na-zona-sul-de-sp.html |title=Pombo com celular \u00e9 encontrado em penitenci\u00e1ria na Zona Sul de SP (Portuguese) |date=August 4, 2015 |publisher=G1 |accessdate=October 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Animal Exploitation==\nPigeon races are sometimes considered as a type of animal exploitation and against animal welfare, particularly where betting is involved, and animal welfare is regarded as secondary. For example, the animal welfare organisation [[PETA]] criticises Taiwanese owners for flying birds across wide oceans where few reach their destination, claiming a fatality rate of 98%. <ref>[Https://example.org https://support.peta.org/page/4206/action/1] Investigation on Pigeon Races</ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of pigeon breeds]]\n* [[American Show Racer]]\n* [[Dovecote]]\n* [[Homing Chicken]]\n* [[Pigeon intelligence]]\n* [[Pigeon photography]]\n* [[Tippler]]\n* [[Otto J. Zahn]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Lucy M Blanchard, ''Chico, the Story of a Homing Pigeon in the Great War'', Diggory Press, {{ISBN|978-1-84685-039-4}}\n* Carter W. Clarke,  \"Signal Corps Pigeons.\" ''The Military Engineer'' 25.140 (1933): 133-138 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/44563742 Online].\n* [[Jon Day (writer)|Jon Day]], \"Operation Columba\" (review of [[Gordon Corera]], ''Secret Pigeon Service'', William Collins, 2018, 326 pp., {{ISBN|978 0 00 822030 3}}), ''[[London Review of Books]]'', vol. 41, no. 7 (4 April 2019), pp.&nbsp;15\u201316.  \"Pigeons flew across theRoman Empire carrying messages from the margins to the capital.  [In 43 BCE] [[Decimus Junius Brutus Albinus|Decimus Brutus]] broke [[Marc Antony]]'s [[Battle of Mutina|siege of Mutina]] [Modena, in northern Italy] by sending letters to the consuls via pigeon.... [However, p]igeons only really came into their own with modern [times, especially d]uring the 19th and early 20th centuries...\"  ([[Jon Day (writer)|Jon Day]], p.&nbsp;15.) \n* [[Meir Shalev]], ''A Pigeon and a Boy'' (English translation by Evan Fallenberg), a historical novel about the use of pigeons by the [[Israel Defense Force]]s (and the Haganah before Israel was founded in 1948) in the defence of Israel when it was first founded, and in the defence of the Jewish community before Israeli independence\n* [[Jerry Spinelli]], ''Wringer'' \n* {{cite book|last=Tegetmeier|first=William Bernhard|title=The homing or carrier pigeon|year=1871|publisher=George Routledge|location=London}}\n* [http://www.hackemerlofts.com/articles.html \"Nine Champions Create A Champion\"], Bob Kinney Silverado, ''The Thoroughbred'', 15 May 1998\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Homing pigeons}}\n* [http://pigeoncomm.site90.net/ Pigeon and Business and Communication]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051217093543/http://www.txtwriter.com/Onscience/Articles/pigeons.html The great pigeon race disaster of 97 suggests an answer to an enduring mystery], George Johnson, \"ON SCIENCE\", ''[[St. Louis Post Dispatch]]''\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/dirs/1/4/9/9/14990/14990-h/14990-h.htm#art10 The System of Military Dovecotes in Europe] from an 1891 ''[[Scientific American]]'' article at [[Project Gutenberg]]\n* Joao Moreira Tavares: [https://encyclopedia.1914-1918-online.net/article/carrier_pigeons_portugal/ Carrier Pigeons (Portugal)], in: [https://encyclopedia.1914-1918-online.net/home.html/ 1914-1918-online. International Encyclopedia of the First World War].\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090601232918/http://silvio-co.com/pigeons/ Resource for pigeon racers]\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=nCcDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA49 Round Trip War Birds], ''[[Popular Science]]'', November 1941, article on [[US Army Signal Corps]] use of homing pigeons with first high-speed photos showing how a pigeon flies\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Uh8QlfQ26Q Fragment 'Those waiting for the birds'] (2008, Eve Duchemin), documentary about Belgian homing pigeons\n* {{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p-IDAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA195&dq=Popular%20Science%201930%20plane%20%22Popular%20Mechanics%22&pg=PA194#v=onepage&q&f=true |title=The Passing of the Carrier Pigeon|journal=Popular Mechanics |date=February 1930|pages= 194\u2013197|last1=Miller|first1=James Nevin}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Airmail]]\n[[Category:Animal-powered transport]]\n[[Category:Animals in sport]]\n[[Category:Domestic pigeons]]\n[[Category:Pigeon breeds]]\n[[Category:History of telecommunications]]\n[[Category:Pigeon racing]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reference list duplication", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homing_pigeon"}
